commit_message:
added clean_users flag in metadata

For securing rabbitmq setup, its important to delete users like guest.

This flags allows you to do the cleanup of all the remaining users that
are not specified through the metadata.

Change-Id: Ib21592e9d40d1909835ea2ed4987c6cbe7996389

commit_message:
Add task file validate command

* Remove the redundant users context setup from benchmark.engine
* Add task_validate to orchestrator api
* Add verify command to validate the task file:
    rally task validate --deploy-id <deployment> --task <TASK FILE PATH>

Change-Id: I6cccf55cb390ae8bb95716db779a0c6daf965f99

This isn't handling the common-venv/environment.d files the same as the
original dib-run-parts, as a result CI is running a lot slower (no
common venv) and lots of tests are timing out. Switch back to the old
method while we rectify the problem.

commit_message:
Revert "Use dib-run-parts from dib-utils"

This isn't handling the common-venv/environment.d files the same as the
original dib-run-parts, as a result CI is running a lot slower (no
common venv) and lots of tests are timing out. Switch back to the old
method while we rectify the problem.

This reverts commit 644598941c912257cba3aa4221ebfe4953b7c66a.

Change-Id: I2e295e9365f777ba7526a56b2d9db3c11424c3e3

commit_message:
New extension for version 2 of LBaaS API

Also added some constants for supported protocols, algorithms,
health monitor types, and session persistence types.

Partially-implements: blueprint lbaas-api-and-objmodel-improvement

Change-Id: I43270fdf9cd52a57274575ecea502f660ff0d5a9
Co-authored-by: Brandon Logan <brandon.logan@rackspace.com>
Co-authored-by: Vijayendra Bhamidipati <vbhamidipati@paypal.com>

commit_message:
Do not iterate action.choices if it is none

Do not iterate action.choices in the method add_arguments
in the class OpenStackHelpFormatter if action.choices is
not iterable because it is none.

Change-Id: Ie7110adb798326e5856fddfb6a7365c663b84998
Closes-Bug: #1372152

commit_message:
Fix create and user-role-add in LDAP backend

The LDAP backend while generating 'dn' for ldapadd operations
does not add the id attribute in the attributes list
While newer versions of LDAP server support this operatoin,
older ones reported error. Eg. OpenLDAP 2.3

This change set fixes that error by adding the required
attribute in the list to make it compatible with older
LDAP versions

Change-Id: I1ed3f53d325eb280e036fbbf8e83d2e645db53cd
Closes-Bug: #1340041

commit_message:
Switch to static content for glance upload test

glance is able to fetch an image from a given url.
Previously the dashboard main page was used as image,
this change sets it a static image, in order
the have less gate issue.

Any url could be used which does not requires authentication.

Change-Id: I66760790aa7d2d0d7b8c53d62baf59134b9b44d6

commit_message:
Added fix for dependacy for mysql-chef_gem

Bumped the version to 0.0.4 that has a fix for ubuntu ruby191-dev.
The error this resolves is this:
```ruby
        /usr/bin/ruby1.9.1 extconf.rb
/usr/lib/ruby/1.9.1/rubygems/custom_require.rb:36:in `require': cannot load such file -- mkmf (LoadError)
        from /usr/lib/ruby/1.9.1/rubygems/custom_require.rb:36:in `require'
        from extconf.rb:5:in `<main>'
```

Change-Id: Ie86c3ab5f957b2b345df0ed2f1d0d6b610ba2178

commit_message:
make flavors use common limit and marker

Flavors REST calls were not using the common limit and 
marker function, which means that the osapi_max_limit configuration
that was set by the operator would not be respected. 

Convert flavors to use the common infrastructure thereby providing
a more consistent experience for users and operators.

Change-Id: Iabbf74cf14ddab9a67092ba966270a658ce6be3f
Closes-Bug: #1304790

commit_message:
Delete backup created during replication

During replication, backup of the master instance is
taken, and a slave is created using this backup.
This patch cleans up the backup which is created
during this process (irrespective of whether it was
successfully provisioned or not).

Closes-Bug: #1359354
Change-Id: Ic636ffeb0bbfb9e6cc02690efe812ffc11bda85c

commit_message:
Allow unsharing a network used as gateway/floatingip

If network has ports that connect it as gateway to another network, such
as an external network, or "floating ip" ports it should still be
possible to "unshare" it since these ports represent usage of the
network as an external network, not as a VM data network.

Change-Id: Ic33ae7ac193e4fc9fe06a4cfd579a4aacf0e6354
Closes-bug: #1293184
(cherry picked from commit 7a2053c7a27bdec02e97b46736c5fcce5f2d053a)

commit_message:
Early checks for data migration config and headers

Modify data_migration middleware and migration drivers so
that config is checked during middleware initialisation
and container migration headers are checked during container
PUT/POST requests.

Also add unit tests to increase coverage.

Change-Id: Iba532a38b21026559fab55dae1aa06a824c2b854

commit_message:
horizon ignores region for identity service

this change will attempt to use a identity service in the selected region
when available.  before the region for the identity service was always the first
found

Change-Id: Idc64a32128bcee561cdbba956722adad0ee1eaf2
Closes-Bug: #1339382

commit_message:
[WIP] add scenario to test Cinder guarantees

* Cinder guarantees that a delete operation on a
  volume will not succeed until that volume is in
  the available state
* added a create_and_delete_volume_nowait scenario
  which attempts to delete the volume without
  waiting for the create to return that the volume
  is in the available state

Change-Id: Ie802aa750cdc75ba610a2e4f207f115fd13176a0

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-21 15:39:53.000000000', 'message': 'Rework and enable VPNaaS UT for Cisco CSR REST

The Cisco CSR REST client library unit tests were developed in Icehouse,
using the httmock library. However, the community did not want to add this
library to global requirements, as there was a similar httpretty library
available (albeit with some shortcomings). As a result, the test module
was renamed with a "no" prefix, to prevent inclusion in automated tests.

Since then, a new library, requests-mock, has been added to global
requirements, to replace httpretty, and is being used on several other
projects.

This commit does three things. First, it adds requests-mock to
test-requirements.txt for Neutron (there is no other similar library for
Neutron). Second, the unit test module for the Cisco CSR REST client is
re-enabled. Third, that UT module has been reworked to use requests-mock,
instead of httmock.  The functionality is the same, but the mechanism
(a fixture with URI registration vs context manager) is different. This
provides coverage for the REST client code.

Note: the unit tests were designed such that they could be reused by a
module with client test classes that specify a live CSR, instead of using
mock responses. This permits verification of the REST client and UTs on a
real system, and could be used in a Tempest test in the future.

There is a separate review (115107) that has only the first item, adding
requests-mock to test-requirements.txt, if there is a desire to separate
the addition of the library from unit test code that uses the library.
I can either abandon 115107, or remove that contents from this patch set.
Please advise me either way.

Change-Id: I55c8a253eb32985bc2016ae748b1ded58d021e1a
Closes-Bug: 1358470

commit_message:
Rework and enable VPNaaS UT for Cisco CSR REST

The Cisco CSR REST client library unit tests were developed in
Icehouse, using the httmock library. However, the community did
not want to add this library to global requirements, as there was
a similar httpretty library available (albeit with some short-
comings). As a result, the test module was renamed with a "no"
prefix, to prevent inclusion in automated tests.

Since then, a new library, requests-mock, has been added to global
requirements, to replace httpretty, and is being used on several
other projects.

This commit reworks the unit test to use requests-mock, instead of
httmock. The functionality is the same, but the mechanism (a
fixture with URI registration vs context manager) is different.

This commit provides coverage for the REST client code, by using a
mock for the Cisco CSR VM. The unit test module can be subclassed,
and used with a real CSR VM, for 3rd party CI testing, in the
future.

Change-Id: I55c8a253eb32985bc2016ae748b1ded58d021e1a
Closes-Bug: 1358470

commit_message:
Remove unused py33 tox env

It's apparent that Nova is quite a ways from Py3K support, and
developers are not expected to run the py33 tox env. Rather than add
more envs for later Python interpreter versions which will be
equally broken, just remove it for now.

Change-Id: I885e6e8899f771cc52a2bf6282fd7bc1ed3083aa

commit_message:
Changing Hadoop to "Data Processing"

Changing "Hadoop Cluster by Sahara" to
"Data Processing Cluster by Sahara to be more
technically correct for non-hadoop clusters.

Change-Id: I16c0c482a1cec77e206ce9701f9e76aff5ae2402
Closes-Bug: #1371760

commit_message:
Use oslo.utils

Module `importutils` from common code was graduated to oslo.utils,
so it would be great if we reuse this library.
Remove unused strutils.py and gettextutils.py

Change-Id: Iaae19fc5018d83103e5f15ff76d6da686bfdf5f8

commit_message:
Move tripleo-bm-test network to 172.16.0.0/22

We now have enough capacity in one rack to exceed 192.168.1.0/24 so
we agreed at the mid-cycle to scale this up to 172.16.0.0/22 -
allowing room for other uses in the same ip space, but exceeding our
current capacity by a comfortable margin.

Change-Id: I0aa99ec063d9c855e7e49416f0840d3b58a5e202
Co-Authored-By: Derek Higgins <derekh@redhat.com>

commit_message:
HP 3PAR drivers should not claim to have 'infinite' space

The HP 3PAR drivers report 'infinite' space when there is not a limit
set on the CPG. In this case, it would be better to at least use the
free space estimate of the array instead of 'infinite'.

Change-Id: I8c34ea3982fe61a1b6fa01245ca6da23ca5b8b7b
Closes-Bug: 1369057

commit_message:
Add tests for consistency groups DB migration

The consistency group patch added 2 new DB migration versions:
025 and 026. However, there were no unit tests to support them in
cinder/tests/test_migrations.py. This patch added missing tests.

Change-Id: I670825980fddd4b6dc400e5a17e1003ad47ace1a
Closes-Bug: #1370756

commit_message:
Verify requested size in volume.api create

Currently we're not checking that the input value requested
for size on volume create is valid, but taskflow portion of
the code expects it to be and as a result when it receives invalid
input we litter the logs with Trace messages.

This patch adds a check that verifies that if we pass in a
size to create_volume in the volume.api that it is in fact
an int or a string representation of an int.

Worst commit ever

Change-Id: I81bf515360eacf63e6f3cdb672ec7f37001aa4fb
Closes-Bug: 1370773

commit_message:
HP 3PAR: Allow retype when the old snapshot CPG (3PAR pool) is None

A common provisioning group (CPG) is a virtual pool of logical disks.
A volume is stored in a CPG. The volume's snapshots may be stored in
the same CPG or in a separate CPG. In 3PAR this is the "snapCPG".

Before the 3PAR driver supported "manage", the snapCPG was never None in
OpenStack because when we create volumes, we explicitly default snapCPG
to match the volume CPG unless otherwise specified. So, the original
retype pre-checks raised an exception if this unexpected case occurred
and a unit test was provided for that exception.

Now that we support manage_existing(), it should be a valid use case
to manage an existing volume created outside of OpenStack with a snapCPG
set to None. Unfortunately, when we applied volume-type settings to this
volume we would hit that old exception.

That exception has been removed. 

Removing it required the following changes:

1. When retype pre-checks validate the domain of the new snapCPG, it
   will not use the optional old snapCPG. Instead it will compare the
   new snapCPG domain with the old volume CPG domain. This satisfies
   the requirement that domains cannot be mixed and avoids the need
   to have an old snapCPG setting.

2. Remove the no longer used old_snap_cpg parameter and remove the
   code that raised an exception "if not old_snap_cpg".

3. Remove the unit test that was just to test that obsolete exception.

4. Adjust the exiting test_retype_across_snap_cpg_domains to
   verify that a snapCPG domain that does not match the volume
   CPG domain will still raise Invalid3PARDomain

Change-Id: Icd2c66898ef64f81116df102f5529a8da30c14d5

commit_message:
Use right body for test_create_missing_specs_name

Since the test is `test_create_missing_specs_name`, we should define
the the body like `body = {'qos_specs': {'a': 'b'}}`. And add a test
to cover the invalid body case.

Change-Id: Ib1cf9a8b5bfddc0091e28e3765a36c75044642f3
Closes-bug: #1370308

commit_message:
Check replication status failed for non-replication

Need to check self.replication whether is None before the
function get_replication_status be called.

Closes-bug: #1365392

Change-Id: I6f6939a98091e40537f2355bb716b4b3205845e2

commit_message:
Sync latest strutils from oslo-incubator for mask_password fix

This sync pulls in:
   1131b56 Enable mask_password to handle byte code strings

This is the only update since the last sync:
   beca4db Sync latest strutils from oslo-incubator

This is needed to fix a delete volume failure when processutils
calls mask_password with a byte code string.

Change-Id: Ie8a8c8e26abc0e387830bc9246e9a44913ae9b24
Closes-bug: #1368527

    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others

    great way to learn the code base.

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 10146, 'date': '2014-09-10 23:57:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Hi Huang,  Thanks for reviewing this change and noting that this change would be a strict interpretation of the API spec which as currently documented says the values for --all-tenants should be 0 or 1.  The API spec could have specified that the value is a <boolean>.   

When I was making the code changes, I asked John Griffith whether I should allow a <boolean> value (loose interpretation), or permit only those values in the spec.  At that time, he felt that 0 or 1 should be the only allowed values but acknowledge that there isn't a lot of consistency within OpenStack.  I guess the team needs to decide whether the API spec should be changed, or if we should stick with the specific values."}, {'account_id': 10146, 'date': '2014-09-11 00:34:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Just checked in with John, and we'll relax the interpretation for backward compatibility.   I'll update the code to allow the following case insensitive values:  True, False, 1, and 0 Any other values will throw an exception.  Ok ?"}, {'account_id': 10146, 'date': '2014-09-11 19:27:40.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-11 21:39:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified-1

commit_message:
Fix a problem with 'volume list' when 'all_tenants=0'

This change checks the value of 'all_tenants' and returns a list of volumes
for all tenants when 'all_tenants' is 1 (or True). A tenant-specific volume
list is returned when 'all_tenants' is 0 (or False).

An InvalidInput exception is thrown if the 'all_tenants' value is not 0, 1,
True, or False (case insensitive).

Provided new unit tests for the get_all api which check the all_tenants, and
limits parameters.

Fixed pep8 compliance test fails with code being improperly indented, and
changed calls using str() to use six.text_type()

Change-Id: If0b8c343ee7e4e05c9aec89241458dbdf2e4734b
Closes-Bug: #1342046

commit_message:
IBMNAS: Remove call to set r/w permissions to all

During cinder volume create operation from a volume snapshot or
from an existing volume (volume clone operation), the ibmnas
driver sets 'rw' permissions to all, which is unnecessary and
also poses security concerns.
Fixing this issue, removing the calls to set rw permissions to
all during these operations and adding a call to set 'rw'
permissions only to the owner to make sure even if umask is set
at the filesystem level, which might deny 'rw' access to the owner
we explicitely set the required permissions on the volume file.

Change-Id: I0e5ba9262a298e088f7724ddeda3537afa4b023e
Closes-Bug: #1367238

commit_message:
Getting iscsi_ip_address from cinder.conf

In the current version (2.0) of the VMAX driver, we retrieve iSCSI IP
addresses dynamically from SMI-S. However, we ran into situations where
we can't get them reliably during testing. The fix is to get this
information from cinder.conf, just like in version 1.0.

Change-Id: If474f44e99cc45592bacfdec9e1eb2fa48c41e68
Closes-Bug: #1369355

commit_message:
Handle config file with newlines and whitespaces

EMC VMAX driver does not handle newlines and whitespaces
consistently in the XML config file. This patch addressed
this issue.

Change-Id: I45f61f167feee9174ba2bc3229695b680f8e946d
Closes-Bug: #1364232

commit_message:
Ceilometer -- configure vCenter support

Document how to manually configure Ceilometer to report
vCenter metering information.
This could be written up just as a work-around to the bug
but customers are requesting this information so I put the
instructions in the OpsGuide.

An entry in "Known Issues" links to the Ops Guide section.

Change-Id: I7cbe299a79b75f7acdc25b2b655930eb470bdcee
Partial-Bug: 1370700

commit_message:
Fix auth_token for old oslo.config

When running with a havana-level of oslo.config (<1.3.0),
applications with any config options in their api-paste.ini will
fail to start with an error like

 'StrOpt' object has no attribute 'type'

This is because the config options didn't have a type attribute
until 1.3.0.

During the grenade test, the havana level of oslo.config is used,
while the master level of keystoneclient is used, and also in the
havana tests the services are still using the keystoneclient
auth_token middleware.

Change-Id: I745c3e04f18941a2d41e191d43f61b926522bb9d
Closes-Bug: #1372422

commit_message:
Put units in paranthesis in Create Flavor form

In the Create/Edit Flavor forms and Project Quota forms:
- Admin -> Flavors -> Create/Edit Flavors
- Identity -> Projects -> Create Projects -> Quota

some of the units need to be enclosed within paranthesis to be
consistent with the way units are represented in other form like:
- Admin -> Images -> Create Image
- Project -> Volumes -> Create Volume

Change-Id: I96cd9f6c4fe46e51f462ff29a45182ded15b76dd
Closes-Bug: #1372029

commit_message:
libvirt: make volume connection info check more clear

Cinder always returns connection_info with item 'data' now, we should
always check this in Nova side. In current logic, missing data in
connection_info can't avoid unnecessary check. This commit twists
little code to make the logic more clear.

Change-Id: I118ddb8f4ae34d8dcb62edf38ffa67ad756f3cd7

The admin needs to get these right or they won't work - entering white space as the key is no more or less wrong than entering any other invalid key, and we don't *know* what keys are valid, so I'm not entirely sure there's much point to this patch. 

A blank value might be a valid value for some backend (unlimited or something)"}, {'account_id': 9236, 'date': '2014-09-17 13:48:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(4 comments)

My feeling is that a variable amount of whitespace is essentially the same as an empty string, in that there's no easy way to distinguish between them in the UI or commandline."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-17 22:35:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of the repository. Please rebase your change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 2759, 'date': '2014-09-18 22:51:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Agree with Duncan, it's almost not possible to tell what key is valid given the infinite possibilities are out there for various backends.  I tend to *not* to validate key or value for now unless there is further proof of this breaking Cinder or causing security issues."}, {'account_id': 4428, 'date': '2014-09-23 05:02:26.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Validate name and key-value for QoS specs

These commands should not be valid -

cinder qos-create " " consumer=back-end " "=" "

cinder qos-key <id> set " "=" "

Validation checks should ensure that non-blank values are entered for
both the QOS spec name and for spec key-value pairs.

Change-Id: I9dda496d5d1f70f543f6f6c417c88cc30d546351
Closes-bug: #1370194

subject: Added Operator API spec for Octavia v0.5
messages:
[{'account_id': 6951, 'date': '2014-09-18 06:54:00.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-18 07:28:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded.

- gate-octavia-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/38/122338/1/check/gate-octavia-pep8/3c15000 : SUCCESS in 3m 33s
- gate-octavia-python26 http://logs.openstack.org/38/122338/1/check/gate-octavia-python26/672e381 : SUCCESS in 2m 56s
- gate-octavia-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/38/122338/1/check/gate-octavia-python27/e2a0dad : SUCCESS in 2m 16s'}, {'account_id': 10850, 'date': '2014-09-18 20:47:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(11 comments)

I see it as an addition to Neutron LBaaS V2 API to allow operators to perform customer support/system maimtenance. So some of my comments are in light of that...'}, {'account_id': 6951, 'date': '2014-09-18 22:34:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(5 comments)

I don't see how else Neutron LBaaS will call Octavia to create load balancers if the API doesn't have it."}, {'account_id': 11685, 'date': '2014-09-19 04:06:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(8 comments)

So this mostly looks like it's a re-hash of the Neutron LBaaS v2 API, but with a more logical hierarchy. This seems like a good place to start-- though I'd like to see some brainstorming (somewhere-- IRC? Mailing list?) for other things that Operators are likely to need so we can nail the most obvious ones first in this API. The most obvious one I can think of has to do with getting a few commands for at least getting information on Amphorae (if not some manipulation there).

What do y'all think?"}, {'account_id': 6951, 'date': '2014-09-19 19:18:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(4 comments)

I agree with you on getting the Amphora details in the API, but I don't think it is necessary to spend a lot of time deciding what else we need in this first bootstrapping because all of those can be added in pretty easily once this gets in, and by other people at the same time."}, {'account_id': 10980, 'date': '2014-09-20 05:25:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

I'm giving this a +1 in the spirit of, let's get something down, build it, and I don't care if we throw it away between 0.5 and 1.0.  We will learn from it, more than commenting until it's perfect.  Waiting until it's perfect means that it'll take so long that we'll be stuck with it.  IMO.

Also, I think that we muddy a lot of decisions by waffling on whether the neutron lbaas spinout will be its own project, or absorbed by Octavia.  Let's nail that down and not rehash "maybe if" that scenario on the fine details.'}, {'account_id': 10850, 'date': '2014-09-22 22:12:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: -Code-Review

I am a bit confused so what we are building is basically:

Neutron LBaaS Rest API -> some internal model -> Octavia Neutron Driver-> Octavia REST API -> Queue -> ...

Why are we not making the Octavia Neutron Drive put things into the queue? Another REST interface doesn't feel necessary for non operator concerns...

Maybe I am still missing what we are trying to achieve"}, {'account_id': 11685, 'date': '2014-09-23 02:38:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(2 comments)

German: It seems to me to be cleaner (ie. better separation of concerns, and less repeated code) if the Neutron LBaaS Octavia driver talks to the Octavia API rather than reaching into Octavia's "guts" as it were to put something on Octavia's queue. This allows us to put less intelligence into the Neutron LBaaS Octavia driver and thus iterate API-related features faster, being less tied to Neutron LBaaS.

Brandon: I don't think it's mentioned in here, but are we versioning this API? (I think we should be!)'}, {'account_id': 11685, 'date': '2014-09-23 02:40:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

Also, German:

While the API here is essentially just a re-hash of the Neutron LBaaS v2 API, very soon it's going to include operator-specific features which are unlikely to ever make it into the Neutron LBaaS API because these will necessarily expose implementation details (since operators need to know them) which are not common among all load balancer vendors. What you're seeing here is a framework with API stuff we can all agree on which will be iterated on as operator features are added. The point is to get started somewhere."}, {'account_id': 11685, 'date': '2014-09-23 02:42:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Er... sorry: Gonna change my vote to -1 until we get versioning here, eh. :)'}, {'account_id': 10980, 'date': '2014-09-23 02:43:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Stephen, I don't think a REST api is really any cleaner than an imported python module.  Both can be documented, and both can be swapped for each other at will.  I.e. there is a middle ground in-between the rest api and "reaching into the internals".

That said, the reason for the API is that to be scalable, we need this to be an "agent" style driver, and the rest api is the rpc to said agent.  THAT precludes importing a module.'}, {'account_id': 6951, 'date': '2014-09-23 03:45:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)

@Stephen, yes it is versioned.  I forgot to put that into the spec but its been in the code since the beginning.

The reasons I have gone with an API that is essentially a User API at this point is:
1) I misread the diagram and spec for 1.0.  I thought the User API was an Octavia User API, but actually it was Neutron LBaaS.  I still think an Octavia User API is better though.
2) 0.5 has no queue, so to actually test 0.5 out end to end, we'd need some way to actually create load balancers.
3) It seems odd that Octavia would have an operator API but no User API functionalities.  The Operator API should at least be able to create entities.
4) It's a more user-friendly standalone interface than any queue, though this is subjective.
5) It's more vendor-like.
6) Doug's reason
7) BONUS: I have an ulterior motive in that this API will eventually become the spun out LBaaS.  To spin out of Neutron there needs to be a comparable alternative ready to go.  I see this as the first steps to getting there.  Killing two birds with one and a quarter stones (The quarter being the small bit of extra work)."}, {'account_id': 6951, 'date': '2014-09-23 03:46:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I forget stupid gerrit comments don't recognize single newlines."}, {'account_id': 11685, 'date': '2014-09-23 04:05:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

Ok, that reasoning seems good to me. Thanks also for the note on versioning.'}, {'account_id': 10850, 'date': '2014-09-23 04:13:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

Brandon, I like your reasoning as well. If we become indeed the drop in replacement for Neutron LBaaS we are good. Otherwise, I am still convinced that a queue is cleaner -- (I still think Neutron LBaaS v2 has legs so no +2 for now)'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-23 04:42:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

Starting gate jobs.
http://status.openstack.org/zuul/'}, {'account_id': 10980, 'date': '2014-09-23 04:42:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-23 04:47:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+2

Build succeeded.

Improve documentation build

Fix some problems found during documentation build:
* Remove reference to obsolete files
* Fix warning about too short title underlining
* Include api reference in index page
* Include man page in index page
* We have no _static files, so don't set the config option for it
* Fix reference for tests.share

commit_message:
Use oslosphinx

Since manila is now an incubated project, use oslosphinx together with
the incubated theme.
Unset html_static_path since there's currently no static file and sphinx
warns otherwise.

Change-Id: Icfbf2c0ee214da870c3c711a34b6a649e9878659

commit_message:
Enables debug mode for keystone session object

This fixes the lack of debug messages introduced by commit 84af49c.

Change-Id: I7bf3e98c21f09bd4f3c2d5d3bc372f60d717c9d5

commit_message:
Fixes Error Calling GET on V1 Registry

Calling GET on members in the glance registry no longer returns a
500 Server Error. Since GET isn't supported, it now returns a
405 Method Not Allowed, matching the behavior of members for the
glance api.

Change-Id: I25d7e5f4818a1cdb20788643ae6dd7e277928743
Closes-Bug: #1187395

[{'created': '2014-08-27 15:41:38.000000000', 'message': 'Use oslo.serialization

Since module `jsonutils` from common code is graduated in

commit_message:
Use oslo.serialization

Since module `jsonutils` from common code is graduated in
`oslo.serialization`, we should remove code from oslo-incubator and use this
library.

Change-Id: Ia8b5ef598ff415cdde19f523a36a552918f9f94b

commit_message:
Provide ability to build images for other architectures

Adds binaries specified by user to chroot environment
allowing to build  images on amd64,i386,armhf,arm64
architectures.
Closes-Bug: #1332458
Change-Id: If6e63a472ee85559b93b5e6b96d9c3ddcf7bcc98

commit_message:
Update glance configuration file permission

Some of glance configuration files contain secrete information like
qpid_password,db connection. To avoid unauthorized users to access it,
change those file permission to 640.

Closes-Bug:#1372330
Change-Id: I556241f09592d82d796de64b76332addc0f81558

commit_message:
Fix .push python-ibm-db-django polluting common attribute

A Common attribute was having a dashboard specific package added to it.
This has side effects as it will effect other cookbooks using that attribute.

* Create attrbute to hold dashboard specific database packages
* Tests unchanged as they are still correct outcome

Change-Id: I9dae9dfc7a118203a80492160514cbf7d0f975e9
Closes-Bug: #1364508

The provider actions where capturing the keystone cmd error and just
logging them as errors to the log, resulting in a converged node that

Closes-Bug: #1370678

commit_message:
Register provider succeeds when failures occur

The provider actions where capturing the keystone cmd error and just
logging them as errors to the log, resulting in a converged node that
is unusable.  These errors should be raised as exceptions to allow
for these configuration errors to be debugged earlier.

Change-Id: I0990dc8386f5999dc96b6cedfca86a762f031953
Closes-Bug: #1370678

commit_message:
Add sensitive flag to openrc resource

Use to ensure that sensitive resource data is not logged by the chef-client.
Need to update Foodcritic to 4.0 to handle new sensitive attribute.

Change-Id: Ibc115969278f58e8baa01fb7f20303f88aa2ded5
Closes-Bug: #1365113

commit_message:
NSX plugin: set VNIC_TYPE port binding attribute

A recent change has made this attribute required for nova
integration.
This patch adds this attribute to responses generated by the NSX
plugin, and also ensures relevant unit tests are executed for the
vmware NSX plugin.

Change-Id: Ieebab01b406909f66a40cc683763292a9ef6f218
Closes-Bug: #1370112

commit_message:
Backward compatibility to credentials in conf

Before switching to the YAML based configuration as the default for
credentials, we need to introduce backward compatibility to allow
credentials to be configured in tempest.conf.

Partially implements bp:test-accounts

Change-Id: I29c66c87d02f442b1d5b0b2d7c82ff2a140c111f

commit_message:
Disable cinder with ironic

Cinder doesn't currently work with ironic as volumes cannot yet
be attached to baremetal nodes. This is something that may be
available in the K series. For now, though, so that we can work
on enabling the tempest API and scenario tests with ironic, we
need to disable cinder.

Change-Id: I783d3c8539acc2e74922a8aad98f0c7928b3815e

commit_message:
Ensure requirements-py2 is synced

PBR supports files of the style requirements-pyN where N is the
bundling python version, which means we need to sync the same number
of supported possible PBR files that can exist.

This adds in the missing py2 that was not being synced even though
it is a viable requirements file for PBR.

Fixes bug 1371936

Change-Id: I7956d77c275694cf09971766d16af054d2692261

commit_message:
Update the requirements-py2.txt file

It appears the openstack requirements proposal bot
does not currently update all the right files, this
bug is filed @ bug 1371936 so until that is fixed
this proposes the same change to the py2 requirements
file that just got merged into the py3 file.

Change-Id: I03dfc1579f44f930acaf92ef47c13829ffcbf35b

commit_message:
Allow WBE request transition timeout to be dynamic

To enable longer (or shorter) timeouts for a WBE submitted
request to transition out of the (PENDING, WAITING) states
allow the transition timeout that was previously set to 60
seconds to be provided as a WBE configuration option (it
still defaults to the previously fixed 60 seconds when it
is not provided).

Fixes bug 1356002

commit_message:
Record instance faults during boot process

Once a build makes it to the compute manager build_and_run_instance
method no instance faults were being recorded.  This stores the instance
faults appropriately when an instance is placed into the ERROR state.

Change-Id: I348b539d0b5874bac3f7443e6dd4524264ce9766
Closes-Bug: #1355922

commit_message:
Reject WBE messages if they can't be put in an ack state

Attempt to reject messages that could not be acknowledged
so that those messages could be resent (requeueing is not
appropriate since it will just cause the message to come
back).

Fixes bug 1364543

Change-Id: I2cb33b39be950528fa9e22d9a11722bedd0927aa

commit_message:
Color some of the states depending on there meaning

Instead of just having black text color adjust some of the
states text color depending on there type/name and highlight
some as red, green, orange depending on there underlying
meaning.

Color names are from:

http://www.graphviz.org/doc/info/colors.html

commit_message:
LOG which requeue filter callback failed

When a requeue filter fails being called instead of just
logging the exception and traceback also log the callback
index which failed and the string representation of the
callback that failed so that when/if it is later examined to
determine the root cause these pieces of output can be used
to isolate the failing callback.

Also includes a drive-by commit to update the add requeue
filter callback documentation to explain what the callback
will be provided and expected to return.

Change-Id: Idf1ae63cfa706551ac0361e802f3b082783e0b9d

commit_message:
Updating documentation for overview/details

Sahara communicates with the following services:
Heat, Cinder, Neutron and Ceilometer
These services are documented in rationale/details section.

Change-Id: I0d88397c02742e111b46ab525b489f8b8dbd29c4
Closes-Bug: #1350063
backport: none

commit_message:
Run all jobs with mod_wsgi services.

This is a test change to check if running all services (keystone) under
mod_wsgi makes all of the devstack tempest jobs faster.

Change-Id: Ifd9deffd0a75f073c38d71094f1a24c2f36f93c2

subject: Test all tempest jobs without mod_wsgi services

commit_message:
Test all tempest jobs without mod_wsgi services

Do not allow any services (keystone) to run under mod_wsgi. This is a
test change to check if this makes all jobs significantly slower.

Change-Id: I90ddbf67de6574b4e76f8b112971550db2123971

commit_message:
Add default arguments for Connection class

The fakelibvirt.Connection class, among other things, mocks
libvirt.virConnect which doesn't require any parameters. This is
causing a test to fail.

Change-Id: If77864cb0d0bd1dae20b490b8e87a32a0951b52e
Closes-Bug: 1257876
(cherry picked from commit aded4a72b70d936df2771d1a6d35dd71e356de71)

commit_message:
Add reference to neutronincubator project

The Neutron Incubator project is a common place for the Neutron team to
incubate API and service extensions prior to declaring the extension
stable. The incubator will not participate in the integrated
release as items that graduate will be move to an integrated project or
spun out into a new project.

Change-Id: Ib47430d0f9e20801e9e974697e4428083d1b9d19

I think it's a good idea to be forward-thinking like this. I don't have a functional python 3 test environment running yet, but the question I have is:

Is python33 being deprecated?  If so, can we go ahead and just drop it now since nobody is running Octavia right now (and won't be for a while)?"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-05 21:44:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of the repository. Please rebase your change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 10980, 'date': '2014-09-09 00:31:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Workflow-1

We should merge python3 support as soon as its available.  But the env can't even build yet, thanks to eventlet."}, {'account_id': 10980, 'date': '2014-09-09 00:31:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1 -Workflow

Fixing -1'}, {'account_id': 10980, 'date': '2014-09-09 00:31:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Stephen, no py33 is not going anywhere.  It's still the default py3 in ubuntu 14.04, and I'd wager in centos, if there is a py3 there at all."}, {'account_id': 11685, 'date': '2014-09-18 18:12:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-2

I'm gonna -2 this request for now, then."}, {'account_id': 5263, 'date': '2014-09-22 12:48:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Python 3.3 is not the default in Trusty, 3.4 is (which was the reason for proposing this addition). If there's no immediate hope for even 3.3 working though, I'm happy to submit a patch removing it from the tox.ini instead. Would that be preferable?"}, {'account_id': 10980, 'date': '2014-09-22 18:14:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

py34 is also the default in brew, but 33 is still in centos.

py33 is already removed from our tox.ini.

See here for my attempt to remove it from neutron, which did not go well: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/118479/'}, {'account_id': 10850, 'date': '2014-09-22 22:14:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I am on the fence about having eventlet but when I started the discussion on the mailing list there wasn't much helpful commentary what to use instead..."}, {'account_id': 5263, 'date': '2014-09-22 22:56:45.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

Indeed it does seem that py33 has been removed from your tox.ini since I proposed this addition... which explains Zuul's merge-check marking this as a failure a couple days after I uploaded it. ;)"}]

commit_message:
Add pip-missing-reqs tox env

It checks that all of the imported from sahara requirements directly
specified in the requirements.txt file. It's needed to keep all of our
requirements corresponding to imports in code.

Sample output - https://gist.github.com/Frostman/bbc00bd386f317a1160e

Change-Id: I7f792fb59b07eb1a6cb7cd51a1ff0e759da6f68c

[{'created': '2014-09-19 18:28:09.000000000', 'message': "Add genconfig tox env

It'll generate the config sample to etc/sahara/

It could be used by developers to generate the latest version of config
to avoid pep8 check errors (pep8 checks that config is fresh).

Change-Id: Ia942d2558317ae5aa46fce4e869ef0323758210d
"}]
commit_message:
Add genconfig tox env

It'll generate the config sample to etc/sahara/

It could be used by developers to generate the latest version of config
to avoid pep8 check errors (pep8 checks that config is fresh).

Change-Id: Ia942d2558317ae5aa46fce4e869ef0323758210d

was done using _dn_to_id. While this works, that method should be

commit_message:
Fix enabled emulation naming attribute calculation

The calculation for the enabled emulation entry's naming attribute
was done using _dn_to_id. While this works, that method should be
used for calculating the ID for normal user or group entries.

With this change, the enabled emulation entry's naming attribute is
computed when the DN is computed, since in that case the server is
either constructing the DN or getting it from the config.

Change-Id: I795ac428446a67de2794ef71297b4343dbfaf5ea
Related-Bug: #1340041

commit_message:
ironic/baremetal: add validation of host manager/state APIs

Add tests to ensure the ironic & baremetal HostManager and
HostState sub-classes comply with the API contract defined
in their parent class.

Related-bug: #1369151

commit_message:
New extension for version 2 of LBaaS API

Also added some constants for supported protocols, algorithms,
health monitor types, and session persistence types.

Partially-implements: blueprint lbaas-api-and-objmodel-improvement

Change-Id: I43270fdf9cd52a57274575ecea502f660ff0d5a9
Co-authored-by: Brandon Logan <brandon.logan@rackspace.com>
Co-authored-by: Vijayendra Bhamidipati <vbhamidipati@paypal.com>

commit_message:
Initial creation of db models, modules, and tests

Added sqlalchemy models mirroring initial migration
Added engine and session methods based off oslo.db
Added base db test based off of oslo.db
Added model tests
Added data models
Added data model tests
Added migration for one to many load balancer to amphora
Added migration for name and URL size changes
Added smarter comparison method for data models

Implements: blueprint initial-db-models

Change-Id: I8421093f0952d5e3ef287bfd4979cc5a83af6c09

[{'created': '2014-09-13 19:54:58.000000000', 'message': "Fixing the PYTHONHASHSEED bug with our unittests

Switching from HTTPInternalServerError to HTTPServerError
as Pecan seems to be returning HTTPServerError instead.
For some reason the assertion only fails with specific
PYTHONHASHSEED's. As a result, I'm just making sure we
assert against the returned exception to correct the
issue for the moment.

Change-Id: Iad15fa17fc2c4d5c3642462df25e702aaff4801f
Partial-bug: #1348818
"}]
commit_message:
Fixing the PYTHONHASHSEED bug with our unittests

Switching from HTTPInternalServerError to HTTPServerError
as Pecan seems to be returning HTTPServerError instead.
For some reason the assertion only fails with specific
PYTHONHASHSEED's. As a result, I'm just making sure we
assert against the returned exception to correct the
issue for the moment.

Change-Id: Iad15fa17fc2c4d5c3642462df25e702aaff4801f
Partial-bug: #1348818

commit_message:
Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910

commit_message:
Update H501 to check for self.__dict__

There was a bug in Cinder where log formatting
of a translated i18n message with self.__dict__
caused the cinder API service to hang on py26.

Update the hacking rule for locals() in formatting
operations to also check for usage of self.__dict__.

Change-Id: Ie358c4140471b776fecb3430e0131e5b80382689
Closes-Bug: #1366031
Related-Bug: #1365901

commit_message:
Added check for Cinder services

After cluster nodes restart, volumes creation are failed
for several minutes because cinder services are down
due to rabbitmq is not ready yet. We need wait until
cinder-scheduler and cinder-volumes are up on controllers
before doing OSTF tests.

Change-Id: Ie9c35368e0f5e399ee2fe69c7132a4232fe40690
Closes-Bug: #1363994

commit_message:
Fix post_install.d for Fedora distribution

Reasons:
 - Fedora is not Ubuntu
 - Fedora uses 'yum' for software management

Changes:
 - renaming file '90-apt-get-update' to '90-yum-update'
 - swapping 'apt-get update' to 'yum update'

Change-Id: I212ab76ff6e302efcc955d26b7b1d978e4f204ca
Closes-Bug: #1371210

commit_message:
Fix high CPU usage in VMs when RBD images are used

http://www.sebastien-han.fr/blog/2013/08/12/openstack-unexplained-high-cpu-load-on-compute-nodes

[{'created': '2014-09-07 19:49:57.000000000', 'message': 'Add USE_IRONIC_NOVA_DRIVER option

Adds a new option to switch on the ability to use the new
Ironic nova driver location (in the Nova driver tree).

In order for this to work we need to expose some new
heat parameters here:

 Ib48a6b6d8a6cff157bdf3948bd0330e9b29dd46a (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/119472/)

We also need to update the nova.conf template to support the setting
scheduler_host_manager (previously hard coded):

 Id4ca7f90cd85129727e65d0d09f274f3a00d4ebe (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/119633/)

The change is backwards compatible and defaults to using the old Ironic
Nova compute driver for now as to not break anything.

Change-Id: I1138ac7c0000db41eceee9420cbd54c9cacf922d

commit_message:
Seed: use Nova compute Ironic driver

Updates the seed configuration to use the new in-tree Ironic
driver directly. This avoids using the old Ironic driver
which is now deprecated (causing error messages)

Change-Id: I1138ac7c0000db41eceee9420cbd54c9cacf922d

what will happen if we have 2 atomic actions in one benchmarks with same name?'}, {'account_id': 8507, 'date': '2014-08-24 14:34:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

@Boris,

the issue with repeated atomic actions is known to me, but in this patch, I haven't changed anything in this aspect. The fact is that the current implementation just ignores the potential presence of multiple atomic actions of the same name in a single benchmark run - it just retrieves the first atomic action with that name, see e.g.: https://github.com/stackforge/rally/blob/master/rally/cmd/commands/task.py#L146-L161

I agree that this issue should be somehow treated, but I suggest doing that in a separate path, since this piece of work already got +2 from two cores and could be quickly merged.

I would like not to refuse on using dictionaries for atomic actions, so as a workaround, I'd suggest making the next patch that would store repeated atomic actions in the same dictionary but using different keys, e.g. "some_atomic_action (1)", "some_atomic_action (2)" etc.'}, {'account_id': 8507, 'date': '2014-08-24 16:26:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

... or, what seems to be more elegant, enable lists of duration values in the atomic action dict.'}, {'account_id': 8507, 'date': '2014-08-24 22:03:50.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 10.'}, {'account_id': 8507, 'date': '2014-08-24 22:17:27.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 11.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-24 22:42:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Verified-1

Okay, just to explain one more time what this patch does: let's imagine you have a benchmark scenario 'test' that goes like this: http://paste.openstack.org/show/114113/

And you set up the task so that it gets called 20 times.

Without this patch, the output will be: http://paste.openstack.org/show/114111/

But with this patch: http://paste.openstack.org/show/114112/

So, basically two major improvements:
1. We now store info about even those atomic actions that failed ('atomic_action_2' in the example above)
2. We take into account repeated atomic action calls ('atomic_action_1' in the example above)"}, {'account_id': 8507, 'date': '2014-09-22 12:38:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 22:

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-05 11:02:24.000000000', 'message': 'Add atomic action names tracking

Here we change the format of the scenario results so that it now stores
the list of names of its atomic actions in a separate field:

    Before:

        {
            "duration": ...,
            "error": ...,
            "atomic_actions": [{"action": "a1", "duration": 0.3},
                               {"action": "a2", "duration": 0.1}],
            ...
        }

    After:

        {
            "duration": ...,
            "error": ...,
            "atomic_actions": {"names": ["a1", "a2"],
                               "data": [{"action": "a1", "duration": 0.3},
                                        {"action": "a2", "duration": 0.1}]
                              },
            ...
        }

This allows us to solve 2 problems:

1. The statistics table that shows up in the CLI after benchmarks comlete now
   always has rows for all the atomic actions that were invoked in benchmark
   scenarios. Before this patch, this was not the case since occasionally the
   atomic actions data could not be written due to Exceptions.

2. We've removed lots of ugly code in benchmark/processing/plot.py, since now
   there is no need to make passes through the atomic actions data to collect
   their names.

Change-Id: I17f563051bd1c2ec2fb47a385d4cc652895e1f9e

                    {"action": "a1", "duration": 0.3},
                    {"action": "a2", "duration": 0.1}
                ]
            },
            ...
        }

This allows us to solve 2 problems:

1. The statistics table that shows up in the CLI after benchmarks complete now
   always has rows for all the atomic actions that were invoked in benchmark
   scenarios. Before this patch, this was not the case since occasionally the
   atomic actions data could not be written due to Exceptions.

2. We've removed lots of ugly code in benchmark/processing/plot.py, since now

commit_message:
Add atomic action names tracking

Here we change the format of the scenario results so that it now stores
the atomic actions data as a dict:

    Before:
        {
            "duration": ...,
            "error": ...,
            "atomic_actions": [
                {"action": "a1", "duration": 0.3},
                {"action": "a2", "duration": 0.1},
                {"action": "a1", "duration": 0.25}
            ],
            ...
        }

    After:
        {
            "duration": ...,
            "error": ...,
            "atomic_actions": {
                "a1": 0.3,
                "a1 (2)": 0.25,
                "a2": 0.1
            },
            ...
        }

We also solve 2 connected problems here:

1. The statistics table that shows up in the CLI after benchmarks complete now
   always has rows for all the atomic actions that were invoked in benchmark
   scenarios. Before this patch, this was not the case since occasionally the
   atomic actions data could not be written due to Exceptions.

2. We've removed lots of ugly code in benchmark/processing/plot.py, since now
   there is no need to make passes through the atomic actions data to collect
   their names.

This patch also:
* contains some removing of code duplicate between plot & CLI output generation;
* adds missing UTs for raw benchmark data processing;
* fixes a minor bug in histograms bins number calculation.

Change-Id: I17f563051bd1c2ec2fb47a385d4cc652895e1f9e

commit_message:
Add unit test for glanceclient ssl options

Commit 0fe6997856ae39afcbed0ad53cc2916ec369c9d5 added code to pass ssl
options when creating the glance client but was missing a unit test.

Related-Bug: #1279381

Change-Id: Iaf1b8e59d98382c630b8e4e13234b9028a873482

commit_message:
Handle @s in log file names by renaming them

Rabbit log files are bad and use @ in the filename. Replace @ with _at_
to prevent the log server from 404ing on these files.

Change-Id: I6daaf0475b1dab6bcd56c4d838f4600271d6a8be

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-15 10:15:10.000000000', 'message': 'NIST: increase RSA key length to 2048 bit

According to NIST 800-131A, RSA key lenght for digital signature
must >= 2048 bit. Now we use 1024 bit key to generate x509 cert
file. Need to increase the key length to 2048 bit.

Change-Id: I59f614b5d8a79f9e0a96503867cfca176be5c757
Closes-Bug: 1369487
'}]
commit_message:
NIST: increase RSA key length to 2048 bit

According to NIST 800-131A, RSA key lenght for digital signature
must >= 2048 bit. Now we use 1024 bit key to generate x509 cert
file. Need to increase the key length to 2048 bit.

Change-Id: I59f614b5d8a79f9e0a96503867cfca176be5c757
Closes-Bug: 1369487

commit_message:
Added fix for dependacy for mysql-chef_gem

Bumped the version to 0.0.4 that has a fix for ubuntu ruby191-dev.
The error this resolves is this:
```ruby
        /usr/bin/ruby1.9.1 extconf.rb
/usr/lib/ruby/1.9.1/rubygems/custom_require.rb:36:in `require': cannot load such file -- mkmf (LoadError)
	from /usr/lib/ruby/1.9.1/rubygems/custom_require.rb:36:in `require'
	from extconf.rb:5:in `<main>'
```

Change-Id: I8a6d8f06d97cd5adfe40c9cbde13b10bd3d58f1e

commit_message:
Fix ansible element to build standalone

The ansible element relies on many libraries and tools that tend to be
present when OpenStack components are built. However, this makes it work
standalone without any other elements.

Change-Id: I6c1b1d2e2d975ba49102998d48d5aa87efec002b

commit_message:
Updates API name

Zaqar is a messaging service which provides support for different
messaging patterns and messaging related semantics.
This fix changes the old API name -queuing- to a more accurate name, -messaging-.

Change-Id: Icaf67607de962217819f8040abca7dd9b81aa1d4

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-13 07:53:28.000000000', 'message': "Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910

commit_message:
Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Closes-Bug: #1368910

commit_message:
Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Closes-Bug: #1368910

commit_message:
Add a pep8 testenv

To allow us to start thinking about using bashate for our scripts, I've
added a pep8 testenv, which runs bashate and only bashate. The confusing
name is because we expect to add flake8 to this environment later, and
we want the name to be consistent with other projects.

Currently I'm seeing 419 errors; largely trailing whitespace,
indentation, and function calls using the 'wrong' format.

Change-Id: Ibc04e00d4278e3656e1e5981a6c1b646cd61f39f

commit_message:
Add pkg-map to swift-ring element dependency file

Currently swift-ring makes use of the pkg-map element when
installing various packages. As a result of this, pkg-map should
be added to the element-deps file.

Change-Id: I229a7022919a0f748977d93025c35d2a93a75e3b

Fix a bug in datasource driver poll_time

The previous version did not convert the string to an int, so the driver
would poll only once if datasources.conf contains poll_time

Change-Id: Ic7638cf713d0111eb6512ce41779682460521c8a

commit_message:
Neutron DHCP implementation to raise exception if no ports have VIF

Currently only warning is risen, though deploy can't succeed in this
case for both PXE and Agent drivers.

Change-Id: If57a33818f5da820277c94b7b0ae642d29a698ce
Closes-Bug: #1362060

commit_message:
Enable Neutron VPN as Service

Add a recipe, related attribute/template, and unit tests to
to install, configure and start VPN service.
Stop L3 agent if VPN is enabled.

Change-Id: I63322e3c43e38444163371636cbab2c3bbdeaacf
Implements: Blueprint neutron-vpnaas-enablement

commit_message:
Handle VolumeBDMPathNotFound in _get_disk_over_committed_size_total

This handles the VolumeBDMPathNotFound error bubbling up from
_get_instance_disk_info during the update_available_resource periodic
task.

Related-Bug: #1371677

Change-Id: I10c20f3f5f96003fe69fcdc9133c661e6dc009b4

commit_message:
Add some authtoken related attributes

This change adds some attributes into the cookbook so
that they are configurable. It mainly includes:
cafile, memcached_servers, memcache_security_strategy,
memcache_secret_key, insecure and hash_algorithms.

Change-Id: Ic48bd7193815185f1c065c1bd689d67de325cd8e
Closes-Bug: #1371421

commit_message:
Do not set the context twice when forming RPC objects

The context is already being set once the object is instantiated so
there's no need to set it again. This patch fixes that and update tests
to validate if the right context has been added to the object.

Change-Id: I7eb3d734a990eb70e4fbfce6c539b268900b5241
Partial-Bug: #1314732

commit_message:
Handle SNMP exception error.PySnmpError

In ironic.drivers.modules.snmp.py, SNMPClient._get_transport() could
raise an SNMP exception. This is now caught and the ironic exception
SNMPFailure is raised instead.

Change-Id: I8816729b1b9483c213bb9e94b0816a88e609a91d
Partial-Bug: #1267693

commit_message:
Add some authtoken related attributes

This change adds some attributes into the cookbook so
that they are configurable. It mainly includes:
cafile, memcached_servers, memcache_security_strategy,
memcache_secret_key, insecure and hash_algorithms.

Change-Id: I6d38db321da2d86265bace3d36c68ddcb196ed61
Closes-Bug: #1372315

commit_message:
Handle volume bdm not found in lvm.get_volume_size

We're stack tracing in successful gate runs because of a race when
deleting an instance and when the update_available_resource periodic
task is running.

When we hit the race, the volume that's backing the instance is deleted
and the periodic task (virt driver) is trying to get the current
information about the volume, which no longer exists and we fail and
short-circuit the update_available_resource task.

This change adds a decorator which checks if a ProcessExecutionError is
due to the device no longer existing and if so, raises
VolumeBDMPathNotFound, and applies that decorator to the get_volume_size
method.

Related-Bug: #1371677

commit_message:
Configurable token hashing algorithm

The Keystone server and auth_token middleware were enhanced to
support a configurable hash algorithm.

With this change, the user can set

 KEYSTONE_TOKEN_HASH_ALGORITHM=sha256

in their localrc to use the SHA256 algorithm rather than the
default md5. Any hash algorithm supported by Python's hashlib can
be used. The MD5 algorithm doesn't provide enough protection from
hash collisions and some security standards mandate a SHA2 hash
algorithm.

Change-Id: I8b373291ceb760a03c4c14aebfeb53d8d0dfbcc1
Closes-Bug: #1174499

commit_message:
Function for auth_token middleware config

Each project was configuring the auth_token middleware using several
lines of inisets. Since all the projects should configure the
auth_token middleware in the same way create a function and call it.

Change-Id: I3b6727d5a3bdc0ca600d8faa23bc6db32bb32260

commit_message:
Handle correctly protocol 'ANY' in firewall rule

Currently horizon allows to create firewall rule with protocol == 'ANY'
but horizon crashs if you try to update such rule because UpdateRule
assumes that protocol is a string and fails to convert it to uppercase
if protocol is ANY/None. Moreover horizon does not allow to update
protocol to 'ANY' despite neutron supports it.

This change updates UpdateRule in order to convert correctly ANY to
None and vice versa. It allows also to update firewall rule protocol to
ANY.

Closes-Bug: #1324382
Closes-Bug: #1370485
Change-Id: I5748b8e6c1cf0ef0d7a4317016492e064b5e8918

commit_message:
Enable glance keystone authtoken configurations

This patch is for allowing cafile, insecure,
memcached_servers, memcache_security_strategy,
memcache_secret_key and hash_algorithms to be
configurable.

Change-Id: I93e490a1d1378bc1efce16337ed45f93fc7e758b
Closes-Bug: #1370908

commit_message:
Add some authtoken related attributes

This change adds some attributes into the cookbook so
that they are configurable. It mainly includes:
cafile, memcached_servers, memcache_security_strategy,
memcache_secret_key, insecure and hash_algorithms.

Change-Id: I97877cf5ce48bd70b9cb2ff12b1fdffbd5a7a69d
Closes-Bug: #1371438

commit_message:
Allow hash_algorithm to be configurable

We may want to set hash_algorithm to be 'sha2', so we
should allow hash_algorithm to be configurable.

Change-Id: I9be1afb1df9705f5d96c5c3c1caf4f5e4b563042
Closes-Bug: #1370825

commit_message:
Big Switch: Pass tenant names to backend

Records the received tenant names corresponding to tenant IDs
received in requests to a DB. This DB is then referenced
whenever providing a tenant_id in a port or network request to
the backend so the tenant_name can also be included if it is
available.

Implements: blueprint bigswitch-tenantnames
Change-Id: I18882dab057c0040ad56f99f68c5a7a95a8184b4

commit_message:
Making section id names readable in security guide

In the security guide, the section id names are the chapter name
with a random id number on the end. This is harder to work with and not
really necessary. Replacing random id number with actual section names.

Changing the ids at the section definitions for all the sections throughout.
References to these ids are also updated.

Change-Id: Id4aa5df8c7c025ae7a812f1b031041b14002c030
Closes-bug: #1340388

commit_message:
Keep sensitive information out of node attributes

Sensitive information stored in data bags (such as passwords) should
not be stored as node attributes, because they are persisted back to
the server and can therefore be easily retrieved.

Change-Id: I26c1fc1d49a86d8f9ccb6f1a80af90a781c1a80c

commit_message:
Update to latest oslo.vmware

The new release contains the following changes:
* Fix seek and tell in BlockingQueue
* Add DuplicateName exception
* Add ‚Äòdetails‚Äô property to VMwareDriverException
* Enable oslo.i18n for oslo.vmware
* Add API to enable calling module to register an exception
* Imported Translations from Transifex
* Add docs target and generate api docs
* Updated from global requirements
* Work toward Python 3.4 support and testing
* warn against sorting requirements
* Add exception for TaskInProgress
* Updated from global requirements
* Refactoring to reduce noise in log files
* Imported Translations from Transifex
* Add missing session parameter to get_summary
* Updated from global requirements
* Switch off caching to prevent cache poisoning by local attacker
* Support for copying streamOptimized disk to file
* Add support for the DatastoreURL object
* Add methods to the Datastore objects
* Imported Translations from Transifex
* Add Pylint testenv environment

Needed by review https://review.openstack.org/#/c/121479/ which is for bug 1369463

Related-Bug: #1369463
Closes-Bug: #1341954
Change-Id: I281c76f0010ca705e4159e1036712d7c08983412

commit_message:
Add info about pysaml2 into federation docs.

pysaml2 is only required for Keystone2Keystone federation. Due to code
structure, ``pysaml2`` needs to be installed in order to enable
federation extension. Since federation is an extension all the
dependencies are not in the requirements.txt file and will not be
installed by default. This patch updates federation docs adding
information that the library must be installed by hand.

Change-Id: Icc0b3b5cc0e22950a85bb58bbd3631c911be8621

commit_message:
Update invalid state error message on reboot API

This change adds more detail to the error message
when a request to soft reboot an instance in an
invalid state fails, indicating that specifically
soft reboot is the request that failed, when
a hard reboot might still succeed.

Closes-Bug: 1365683

Change-Id: I4b12aa261d1c4fa05bacd5311793ed6e0478e59b

commit_message:
Adding OSSN-0029 - Neutron FWaaS rule bug

Neutron FWaaS rules lack port restrictions when using a protocol
other than 'tcp' or 'udp', e.g. 'any'.

Closes-bug: #1365961

Change-Id: I14a08e6fc2357bbaeb6a37b28f9f9ecd81390219

Replace Ceilometer ClientException with HTTPException

ClientException was removed from Ceilometer client. Replace it
with HTTPException.

Change-Id: I8707593861939b1218e42ff957171e97e225942f
Closes-bug: #1372416

commit_message:
Make context mandatory when instantiating a RPC object

RPC objects should have a context within it, this patch is making passing
the context mandatory when instantiating the object and is a plumbing
work to remove passing the context later for things like create(),
refresh(), destroy() and save().

Partial-Bug: #1314732
Change-Id: If9b175fa874bcb96c77cf22d176f1111f450f796

commit_message:
Use oslo.serialization

Module `jsonutils` from common code was graduated to oslo.serialization,
so it would be great if we reuse this library.
Remove unused log.py and fileutils.py

Change-Id: Ie7d80df501296b4b06da8c1cc155bcc4b64bfe28

commit_message:
Fix return from list role assignments on KVS

List role assignments calls should return
'inherited_to_projects': 'projects' for an
inherited assignment.
This behavior is not valid on KVS. This patch
fix it and add a test.

Change-Id: I6f33d7226eb617d7e72f0a0be1ee0088a3485749
Closes-Bug: 1360406

commit_message:
Use non-deprecated notification_driver

Designate is using oslo.messaging so it should be
using 'messaging' as its notification driver and not the now deprecated
full python path to the oslo-incubator notification driver.

Change-Id: Ic6896ce2606dd8d86a4c96ff570c51f3db4ac399

And we could pre-split test_api_samples if we really wanted to.

- some of the api sample tests require some extensions to be loaded and others require that some extensions NOT be loaded (as output changes based on what extensions are present). Can this infrastructure handle that?'}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2014-09-16 04:16:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hi Chris!

OK, great questions on both counts. For the first question, I went with this approach mostly because I need a place to set up the functional test environment, and I wanted to do this piecemeal, one thing at a time, instead of one giant patch that changed everything. It would make it easier for me to track the progress I'm making and fix issues as they popped up instead of trying to boil the ocean in one fell swoop.

An example of something I need to handle in a followup patch is the topic of your second question :) I'm not really too keen on creating a test environment for each permutation of the darned API extensions just so we can check the output of what are essentially minimal or minor changes to a particular API response. I'd rather just load up all the extensions and verify the response meets the "all extensions response".

And that's just one of the reasons I wanted to go piecemeal and tackle those problems one at a time as I made progress through the entire directory. The final reason is that due to the run_func_tests.py being a separate test runner, I need to make a corresponding change to our gate jobs in Jenkins Job Builder to run the run_func_tests.py test runner. I can't use the main test runner that uses subunit+testr due to not having any place to do the single test environment setup.

-jay'}, {'account_id': 8412, 'date': '2014-09-16 18:00:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

Hi Jay! I left small inline comment and you have many pep8 errors.'}, {'account_id': 5292, 'date': '2014-09-17 08:03:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Jay - so if we're going to use this to replace the current api sample tests then we do need to do more than just an all extensions configuration as the api samples are used for the documentation. And the documentation has to show different api sample input/output depending on the extension.

However I think you could get 90-95% coverage just with two configurations. One where everything was loaded and one with as much removed as possible except for the plugins that need some other plugins removed."}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2014-09-22 17:05:18.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

I'm going to split the functional test case classes into separate files first and then re-work this. That will allow me to have a much smaller patch to review..."}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-15 22:48:47.000000000', 'message': 'Adds new functional test suite for API samples

The existing functional test suite in Nova (in nova/tests/integrated)
suffers from terrible performance due to it spinning up a Nova
environment containing an API WSGI service endpoint, service daemons
for nova-conductor, nova-compute, nova-consoleauth, and running database
migrations for each test method of every test case class in the
test_api_samples.py test file.

All most of the api samples tests do is issue a simple HTTP request
against the API WSGI service endpoint and compare the results it gets
back to a stored api sample document in doc/api_samples/. It is not a
particularly CPU or memory-intensive test, but due to the framework
creating and recreating the Nova environment over and over, typical
runtimes of the nova/tests/integrated/test_api_samples.py tests can take
more than 5 minutes.

This patch adds a new functional test suite for running these kinds of
tests. It sets up a single Nova environment, loads a database and
fixtures, runs the tests, and then tears down the Nova environment.

This patch just adds tests for flavors and versions, in order to keep
the patch size manageable. The tests themselves have not actually
changed, and the new base test class for the functional tests shares 90%
of the code in the existing nova/tests/integrated/api_sample_test_base
file except the Nova environment is not created and recreated in setUp()
and tearDown() each time a test method is run.

The result is that the tests run in a fraction of the time that the
existing integrated tests run.

Change-Id: Ic5d186e33a3f423a38beb64b485eb7f6467ced29
'}]
commit_message:
Adds new functional test suite for API samples

The existing functional test suite in Nova (in nova/tests/integrated)
suffers from terrible performance due to it spinning up a Nova
environment containing an API WSGI service endpoint, service daemons
for nova-conductor, nova-compute, nova-consoleauth, and running database
migrations for each test method of every test case class in the
test_api_samples.py test file.

All most of the api samples tests do is issue a simple HTTP request
against the API WSGI service endpoint and compare the results it gets
back to a stored api sample document in doc/api_samples/. It is not a
particularly CPU or memory-intensive test, but due to the framework
creating and recreating the Nova environment over and over, typical
runtimes of the nova/tests/integrated/test_api_samples.py tests can take
more than 5 minutes.

This patch adds a new functional test suite for running these kinds of
tests. It sets up a single Nova environment, loads a database and
fixtures, runs the tests, and then tears down the Nova environment.

This patch just adds tests for flavors and versions, in order to keep
the patch size manageable. The tests themselves have not actually
changed, and the new base test class for the functional tests shares 90%
of the code in the existing nova/tests/integrated/api_sample_test_base
file except the Nova environment is not created and recreated in setUp()
and tearDown() each time a test method is run.

The result is that the tests run in a fraction of the time that the
existing integrated tests run.

Change-Id: Ic5d186e33a3f423a38beb64b485eb7f6467ced29

commit_message:
Changed template naming in fuel_agent

Made it using get_or_select_template instead of
get_template from jinja2. It allows to try several
different template names before template loader fails.
The motivation behind is that now we can have
some_ubuntu_1204_x86_64.jinja2
some_ubuntu.jinja2
some.jinja2
templates in order to make profile scheme more flexible.

Change-Id: I504cbeb1670966690887e02201286a3dff952284

commit_message:
Changed image data format in fuel_agent

Made it explicit and clear. User may define as many file
system images as he/she needs. Every image is to have
its own uri, format, container and other metadata. Currently,
it is possible to mix different image formats. For example,
image for a root file system might be an ext4 fs image
while /var image - TAR archive.

Change-Id: Ib957ff62e3613fed1e2826f322a056be7803fa48

commit_message:
Update Endpoint Filter API

A small subset of the Endpoint Filter APIs which pass in project_id
in the URL need to be updated to ensure the filter extension name i.e.
OS-EP-FILTER appear after the string /project/{project_id}.

Change-Id: If1688a4c919ee66e748e87815b72354d2059b399
Closes-Bug: #1362245

commit_message:
Update Endpoint Filter API

A small subset of the Endpoint Filter APIs which pass in project_id
in the URL need to be updated to ensure the filter extension name i.e.
OS-EP-FILTER appears after the string /project/{project_id}.

Furthermore, we need to maintain the original APIs that were defined
in the Icehouse release. See routers.py for more details.

Change-Id: Ic397b0d3a4ac56f7302e19bad3bd851852312858
Closes-Bug: 1362245

commit_message:
Fix using key for ssh

Before this fix manila used only password or private key from default
.ssh directory. In this patch, calling the create function will use
one of this methods for authentication. Authentication is attempted
in the following order of priority:
* The private key;
* Any key we can find through an SSH agent;
* Any "id_rsa" or "id_dsa" key discoverable in ~/.ssh/;
* Plain username/password auth.

Change-Id: I74e00dabe5b5a93fb4fbbdcfef4969971af6d0a7
Closes-Bug: #1369913

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-19 23:19:31.000000000', 'message': "Update neutron content for Juno

I updated neutron content in the installation guide for Juno
as follows:

1) Renamed files and IDs since the guide no longer needs to
   differentiate between the ML2 and OVS plug-ins.
2) Removed prompts specific to MySQL because most distributions
   will use MariaDB.
3) Explicitly created endpoint with 'regionOne' region to avoid
   inconsistent defaults.
4) Replaced 'auth_*' options with 'identity_uri' option.
5) Moved neutron configuration options to [neutron] section in
   nova.conf.
6) Recommended enabling verbose logging.
7) Removed workarounds for Ubuntu 12.04.
8) Removed note about CirrOS lacking support for the DHCP MTU
   option.
9) Explicitly defined flat external network type.
10) Added example command output and updated existing command
    output.
11) Added and updated glossary terms.
12) Implemented changes from the improvements blueprint including
    structure and phrasing.

Change-Id: I13baa94585bb6e8b22d8d79043fc84cbc2514954
Implements: blueprint installation-guide-improvements

commit_message:
Update neutron content for Juno

I updated neutron content in the installation guide for Juno
as follows:

1) Renamed files and IDs since the guide no longer needs to
   differentiate between the ML2 and OVS plug-ins.
2) Removed prompts specific to MySQL because most distributions
   will use MariaDB.
3) Explicitly created endpoint with 'regionOne' region to avoid
   inconsistent defaults.
4) Replaced 'auth_*' options with 'identity_uri' option.
5) Moved neutron configuration options to [neutron] section in
   nova.conf.
6) Recommended enabling verbose logging.
7) Removed workarounds for Ubuntu 12.04.
8) Removed note about CirrOS lacking support for the DHCP MTU
   option.
9) Explicitly defined flat external network type.
10) Added example command output and updated existing command
    output.
11) Added and updated glossary terms.
12) Implemented changes from the improvements blueprint including
    structure and phrasing.

Change-Id: I13baa94585bb6e8b22d8d79043fc84cbc2514954
Implements: blueprint installation-guide-improvements

commit_message:
Split autoscaling.py into separate files.

This patch further splits the autoscaling.py into three individual
modules each of which dedicated to one resource type.  The resulted
files are put into different sub-directories for better namespace
isolation.

Change-Id: Icf9d0e072ae490de558adf62e021042698cb18d0
Implements: partial-blueprint reorg-asg-code

commit_message:
Allow use custom ssh_virt_type when register node

In register_ironic_node, ssh_virt_type is hard coded.
This fixes it.

Change-Id: Ie1b00e0c7baef0e93187e5cb8e252db3aa44e7b4
Closes-Bug: #1367586

commit_message:
Set horizon local_settings before compress

Compress fails because local_settings.py default
value is false. The settings file needs to be
created first.

Change-Id: I142a4d78880c143a13d5e715428a5c0937f33c9a
Closes-Bug: #1364938
blueprint fuel-deploy-juno

commit_message:
Do not pip_install DIB for use with Ironic

pip_install'ing diskimage_builder to use with Ironic is not necessary
any longer, since it is now installed "as a service". Instead, rely on the
preparation devstack will have done by checking for the necessary
executable's availability.

Change-Id: I8ace493299a4b14a000151701da65d7cb05c7cee

commit_message:
Fix getting ssh key if ssh path is not set

Add check for get_key function because it should return tuple,
but can also return None.

Closes-Bug: #1356820

Change-Id: I827a9a24c2decfa245d50d90bdee2b64b59da5b1

commit_message:
Revert "libvirt: reworks configdrive creation"

This reverts commit 228d0221763b12f11ecbacde4db38b1151f96e31.

This commit introduced bug 1369627 (a security vulnerability), as
well as misunderstanding how our image caching works for libvirt.
I think we can achieve the same thing in a much simpler manner.

Change-Id: I7ede9b0f77710869197d9b48c6dd6bbc3087738c

commit_message:
FIX: Fail to remove the logical volume

The logical volume can not be removed when delete VM error. I look at the
code, found that parameter is a list in the libvirt's lvm, but in
imagebackend, parameters passed is a string.

Change-Id: I222f6c5cfe5be63105f2fd8afd7ccd209ca2e5f7
Closes-Bug: #1358552

commit_message:
libvirt: Unnecessary instance.save(s) called

When spawning an instance there may a considerable amount of
instance.save() called. This is not necessary as the compute
manager will update the instance after the spawn method has
successfully completed.

Change-Id: I61610b3869caeb7822eab3f2d09335744b75db28
Closes-bug: #1366548
