commit_message:
Update documentation for using keystone auth

Cleanup and add clarification to the documentation
for using Keystone auth.

Update to refer to auth_token middleware being
distributed as part of the keystomemiddelware project
rather than keystone.

Include capabilities (/info) in the list of reasons
why delay_auth_decision might need to be set in
auth_token middleware config.

Add description of the project_id:user_id format
for container ACLs and emphasize that ids rather than
names should be used since this patch has now merged:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/86430

I like the idea to prevent overlapping containers and objects. However,
when I run swift-dispersion-populate --no-overlap multiple times, it will create new containers/objects, even if the dispersion_coverage is already met. Thus the behavior differs a lot from the current behavior. Is this intended?'}, {'account_id': 7134, 'date': '2014-09-12 14:27:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Christian Thanks for the review. Yes, this is the intended behaviour; so if the conf file specifies a% coverage, running "swift-dispersion populate --no-overlap" b times will result in (a*b)% pure coverage (ie. no overlap of partitions).'}, {'account_id': 6968, 'date': '2014-09-15 09:30:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2

Thanks Lorcan, got it! Code looks good to me.

I will start refactoring swift-dispersion-* to add some tests for these tools (because I think it's important that these tools do what they are expected to do)."}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2014-09-16 16:24:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

@Lorcan code looks fine, thanks. Just to be clear, current behaviour is that each time swift-dispersion-populate is run it will create the same N containers in the same N partitions until the dispersion coverage is achieved.

With your change, each time its run with --no-overlap it will create an additional N containers in N distinct partitions until an additional amount of dispersion-coverage is achieved?

I think the commit message confused me - with current behavior you don't get multiple containers in same partition - you just replace the containers that were already there, one container per partition, right?

Unless, if you increase the dispersion coverage and then run again with --container-suffix-start = N in which case currently it would leave existing containers in place and create new containers that could be in same partitions - is that the problem case?"}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2014-09-16 18:02:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)

Current behavior is that swift-dispersion-populate creates containers/objects to cover some user-specified fraction of the partition space while completely ignoring anything that's already there, so it just gives you a minimum. For example, if you populate with 10% and then populate with 10% again, you could theoretically have anywhere from 10% to 20% coverage with the most probable result being 19% coverage and 1% double-coverage.

This change gives you additive coverage, so populating 10%, 10%, and 5% with --no-overlap will give you 25% coverage instead of coverage in the interval [10%, 25%].

At least, that's what I think it does. I haven't played around with it to verify that claim."}, {'account_id': 7134, 'date': '2014-09-17 10:46:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Alistair Thanks for the comment. My commit message is misleading as it is referring to the old behaviour of swift-dispersion-populate. Additional containers/objects are now, generally no longer created when populate is run. However, as you pointed out, adding a container/object suffix can still result in overlap so this change can still be useful. I can update the commit message to clarify this and will also make the change that Samuel suggested when uploading a new patch'}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2014-09-17 13:09:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Hmm, Lorcan mentioned the 'old version' and I found this change https://review.openstack.org/#/c/45350 where the old behavior sounds like what Sam describes (because the suffixes were uuids you'd get additional containers/objects on each run) but that got changed to monotonically increasing suffixes.

So unless I'm mistaken the current behavior is that each run reproduces the exact same set of containers/objects that were there before (because the suffixes are monotonically increasing from default of 0) i.e. coverage does not increase on each run.

The --no-overlap option added by this patch causes existing container/objects to be left in place and a new set of container/objects to be added (guaranteed to be in distinct partitions) therefore increasing the coverage by whatever dispersion_coverage.

And so this patch puts back something similar (but better) than the 'old' behavior i.e. the possibility of increasing coverage with each run."}, {'account_id': 7134, 'date': '2014-09-17 13:24:35.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 7134, 'date': '2014-09-17 14:45:16.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-17 16:40:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

[{'created': '2014-09-02 17:26:47.000000000', 'message': 'Add "--no-overlap" option to swift-dispersion populate

Currently if "swift-dispersion-populate" is run more that once on
a system, there is a distinct possibility of overlaps of populated
partitions; that is multiple dispersion containers/objects being
found in the same partition. This is an inefficient use of the
tool as it has no advantage over a single object/container in the
partition.

This change allows the user to use a "--no-overlap" parameter when
running the tool so that no partition is populated more than once.

Relates To: Bug_#1233045

Change-Id: I139fed2f4c967ba18d073b7ecd1e946ed4da1271

commit_message:
Add "--no-overlap" option to swift-dispersion populate

This change allows the user to use a "--no-overlap" parameter when
running the tool multiple times. It will increase the coverage by
whatever is specified in the dispersion_coverage field of the conf
file in a manner where existing container/objects are left in place
and no partition is populated more than once.

Related-Bug: #1233045

Change-Id: I139fed2f4c967ba18d073b7ecd1e946ed4da1271

@Kevin L. Mitchell

The major difference between this new feature and host-evacuate is that 'host-evacute' command is targeting failed compute nodes, and will fail for compute nodes that are up. Moreover, destination host for evacuated instances must be given, that result in bypassing the scheduler.

The new host-servers-live-migrate command will be transparent for customer, without any downtime for running instances and if a destination host is not given, the scheduler will be used in order to find proper compute host."}, {'account_id': 679, 'date': '2014-06-23 19:51:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

commit_message:
Live migrate each instance from one host to other hosts

Using the existing server live_migrate api, this new feature,
adds the ability for admins to live-migrate all running instances
from one host to other hosts. The patch implements the feature
for Nova API V2 and API V3.

Co-Authored-By: C√©dric Soulas <cedric.soulas@cloudwatt.com>

Change-Id: Ie8dd1b66fb8eaefa6ff38752b1e4f46bab145820
Implements: blueprint host-servers-live-migrate

There is still an issue that needs to be investigated.
When I create a new domain and then issue a dig request against the bind server for either AXFR or SOA, I still see provisioning.example.com. in the SOA and NS.

I have to either

(1) add a recordset to the domain or
(2) touch the zone file and do an rndc reload.  Without touching the zone file, doing an "rndc reload" states "zone reload up-to-date"'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-08 22:37:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Verified+1

Total guess - But I'll check it out now..."}, {'account_id': 741, 'date': '2014-09-10 13:26:46.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 8.'}, {'account_id': 741, 'date': '2014-09-10 13:27:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

If they come in at different times, then I see the right data with AXFR, if they come in at the same time, then I see the dummy data with AXFR.'}, {'account_id': 741, 'date': '2014-09-18 14:56:08.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 10.'}, {'account_id': 8174, 'date': '2014-09-18 15:47:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Code-Review+1

I think this patch fixes : https://bugs.launchpad.net/designate/+bug/1370621

But it slows down the following curl call :

curl -X PATCH ${base_url}/reverse/floatingips/RegionOne:$FIP_ID -H "X-Auth-Token: $TOKEN" -d '{"floatingip": {"ptrdname": "toto.lol.com." }}' -H "Content-Type: application/json" 

It used to take ~2sec without this patch. Now it takes ~11sec. In my bind9 logs I see the following logs : http://paste.openstack.org/show/x8c5JEKDw3OdF2iX39e3/ The time corresponds with the time I made the curl request.'}, {'account_id': 8094, 'date': '2014-09-18 18:09:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Code-Review+2

Expecting the test to pass - though I wonder if the devstack job now takes much longer to run.

Jordan, unfortunately now in the bind backend, there is pretty much a delay of 1 second to every change to the zone file.  Not doing that could potentially mean that changes that happen in the same second are not loaded by BIND.

Kiall, I am not sure if it is worth tracking the time of the last change and then deciding to sleep based on that.'}, {'account_id': 7350, 'date': '2014-09-18 19:23:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11:

Vinod, I get that we have to sleep 1sec but I haven't figured out why this sleep(1) call is call 10 times. But I guess that's another issue."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-18 19:41:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Verified-1

commit_message:
Backends need to implement c/u/d_recordset

The current code means the central generate SOA/NS records are
not provisioned, nor or any records create via the V2 API.

Closes-Bug: 1366821
Closes-Bug: 1370621

commit_message:
Enable automatic failover of l3 routers

When l3-agent is not working on a node, neutron server will
automatically move its routers to another l3-agent. Neutron server
detects l3-agent outage after 1-2 minutes, neutron-l3-agent is now
monitored every 30s by pacemaker which will restart the service in case of
a failure (this should cover most of outages). If outage is longer
(e.g. networking issue) and routers are reassigned to another node,
l3-agent will clean up routers from local node when it restarts (or when
it can communicate with neutron server again).

This solution is not perfect and doesn't cover some edge situations
described here: https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1174591
But I think this still improves current state of l3-agent HA.

This should not be needed once neutron l3 agent HA patch is merged
(I83f2a5d2af42164c42773b385ba7b00872eed54e).

Change-Id: Ifd8d73b3b1a5b13095e87683449aa4cab7579d3e

commit_message:
WIP - RHEL7 Registration

This element provides support for RHEL 7 instances to register
with Satellite 6 or Red Hat's Customer Portal for package and
errata management.

This is currently a work in progress.

Change-Id: Ia85f0bf2537793f57e3fab71f93c0d10753f80ad

commit_message:
Fix issues with timeout and if a domain exists

* When creating a domain it would fail if the domain exists. New behaviour is
  to update the existing domain.
* Raise default request timeouts to 10

Change-Id: I4896f046feb1cc3382a4a848cb0d0689bed44b5b

commit_message:
Fix stack update for Python API

Change I30a2b223d7dd19a717ed989b419b1e6cb2ac143b
introduced 'existing' keyword to stack-udpate command that became effectively
required argument to stack.update method of the client's Python API,
breaking backward compatibility.

Change-Id: Icda3313805c29ab36773a4edc8c9f8c874b71ca3
Closes-Bug: #1371167

commit_message:
Add helper script for artifacts naming schema.

Naming schema used in our Jenkins setup currently is not specified
anywhere in our docs. Let us define it in the following way::

 Token              Regexp
 fuel               "fuel"
 [-<ci_id>]         "(-(?P<ci_id>(gerrit)|(community)))?"
 [-<version>]       "(-(?P<version>(\d\.\d)|(master)))?"
 [-<art_type>]      "(-(?P<art_type>(upgrade)|(patching)))?"
 [-<build_number>]  "(-(?P<build_number>\d*))?"
 [-<timestamp>]     "(-(?P<timestamp>\d{4}-\d{2}-\d{2}_\d{2}-\d{2}-\d{2}))?"
 .<art_ext>         "(\.(?P<art_ext>[a-z\.]*))\Z"

Helper script can be used to:

* enforce naming policy for future setups and across all Jenkins
  instances via 'test' subcommand (specification by implementation),
* provide data for internal shell scripts with 'parse --fmt <smth>'
  subcommand,
* track all the naming policy changes via usual Git/Gerrit workflow.

Change-Id: Ieb96cd15803f014f85f69b97e14f4c2d69be01fa

commit_message:
labs: wait for namespaces and interfaces

When setting up neutron router and DHCP, the time until namespaces and
interfaces are ready varies a lot (from less than a second to five
seconds and more), even on the same host system. If it takes longer, we
proceed too early which leaves the cluster misconfigured. In that case,
nova instances fail to get a DHCP address.

This patch makes sure the script waits until the interfaces are ready.

Change-Id: I346a098062d984956cf496e89f9ada2a38df0569

[{'created': '2014-09-16 11:17:12.000000000', 'message': "Non-EUI64 fixed IPs should be rejected for IPv6 SLAAC

When a port is created on a subnet that is configured for IPv6 SLAAC,
that port's IP address will be automatically generated (to a
pre-determined value, based on the subnet's IPv6 prefix and the port's
MAC address) using the EUI64 address algorithm. Therefore, any port
create request that includes a fixed IPv6 address that does not match
the expected IPv6 EUI64 address should be rejected.

This change adds a check for any fixed IP addresses that do not match
the expected automatically-generated addresses for port creation on
an IPv6 SLAAC subnet.

This change also removes a check for duplicate address assignment on
IPv6 SLAAC subnets. Duplicate address assignments on IPv6 SLAAC should
be prevented by the following:
- IPv6 prefixes are confirmed to be unique when the subnet is created.
- MAC addresses are confirmed to be unique when a port is created.
- This new change will only allow unique EUI64 addresses (based on
  unique prefix and unique MAC address) to get assigned to a port
  on an IPv6 SLAAC subnet.
(I tried leaving in the existing check for duplicate addresses on
IPv6 SLAAC subnets, but was at a loss as to how to modify the existing
associated unit test to force duplicate addresses, because of the
considerations listed above.)

Change-Id: I986abbad89fe003bbd34804b5143791865607494
Closes-Bug: #1369767
"}]
commit_message:
Non-EUI64 fixed IPs should be rejected for IPv6 SLAAC

When a port is created on a subnet that is configured for IPv6 SLAAC,
that port's IP address will be automatically generated (to a
pre-determined value, based on the subnet's IPv6 prefix and the port's
MAC address) using the EUI64 address algorithm. Therefore, any port
create request that includes a fixed IPv6 address that does not match
the expected IPv6 EUI64 address should be rejected.

This change adds a check for any fixed IP addresses that do not match
the expected automatically-generated addresses for port creation on
an IPv6 SLAAC subnet.

This change also removes a check for duplicate address assignment on
IPv6 SLAAC subnets. Duplicate address assignments on IPv6 SLAAC should
be prevented by the following:
- IPv6 prefixes are confirmed to be unique when the subnet is created.
- MAC addresses are confirmed to be unique when a port is created.
- This new change will only allow unique EUI64 addresses (based on
  unique prefix and unique MAC address) to get assigned to a port
  on an IPv6 SLAAC subnet.
(I tried leaving in the existing check for duplicate addresses on
IPv6 SLAAC subnets, but was at a loss as to how to modify the existing
associated unit test to force duplicate addresses, because of the
considerations listed above.)

Change-Id: I986abbad89fe003bbd34804b5143791865607494
Closes-Bug: #1369767

commit_message:
Do not cache auth token in Neutron DHCP provider

Currently token expire after some time and deploy breaks.
Also refactored all tests for Neutron DHCP provider, as
many of them were just broken (e.g. using non-existing asserts).

Change-Id: I38a8e95a09fd4737682e37b1162eb445fbc8012f
Closes-Bug: #1371503

test db2 driver code

currently, db2 driver code is not being tested. the scenario tests
are essentially calling the mongodb driver code twice.

commit_message:
Fixes 'Same hostname for different instances' bug

Classes that inherit from NetworkManager use the attribute instance_dns_manager
to handle DNS service operations. This attribute is an instance of the class
defined at CONF.instance_dns_manager, that is, by default,
'nova.network.noop_dns_driver.NoopDNSDriver'. Changing the default driver to
'nova.network.minidns.MiniDNS' implies in verifying if a DNS entry name is
unique into the domain before adding the new DNS entry.

DocImpact Any documentation considering NoopDNSDriver as default DNS driver have
to be updated.
UpgradeImpact Existing OpenStack setups in whose there are existing different
instances with the same hostname may be affected when introducing this patch.
Existing instances may be affected by any operation that need to reconfigure
networking on the instance, such as re-sizing or migrating.

Closes-Bug: #1283538

Change-Id: I2fdd8296431b3011b408759ccc63ba136e2f2b16

commit_message:
Fix test not passing due to Nova patch

The test test_create_with_existing_server_name at
tempest/api/compute/servers/test_servers.py is not passing due to
the patch for the bug https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1283538.
This patch prevents the creation of different instances with the
same hostname into the same domain.
For further information, look at the Nova patch review at
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/94252/

Change-Id: I2278a5326c64633dc7afe043c1fc87abb8801f33

commit_message:
labs: set lower MTU for bridge to instance VM

The MTU on the bridge to the instance VMs needs to be lower than 1500 to
compensate for the GRE overhead. With an MTU of 1500, one thing that
fails is ssh authentication (into the instance VM).

This patch does not help for the CirrOS 0.3.2 image which we currently
use, because it is not able to pick up MTU values via DHCP.

Change-Id: I2a04b62beef6120e811f00472aa7395ab3d683dc
Co-Authored-By: Pranav Salunke <dguitarbite@gmail.com>

occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other

commit_message:
Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910

commit_message:
Ported repository installation from puppet-openstack

Ported repository installation from puppet-openstack. Added
error handling for invalid repositories. Using stahnma/epel
to manage EPEL installation EPEL 7. Set repository default
to 'icehouse'.

Change-Id: I6fdbaf1ee59186aba4d2d5945c9297fb5ef94cbb

have been exported.

For OVA export:

commit_message:
labs: fix shared folder restore after export

Fix the code responsible for reattaching shared directories after VMs
have been exported.

For OVA export:
- use saved share names instead of default name (for the sake of
  correctness; it is unlikely that a user will change the name)

For dir export:
- save and reattach shared directories after export

Change-Id: I79162c1ec788aa1d89104aa92aebeae2bb05adf5

labs: set OSBASH for export

Exporting VMs has not worked in a while. We need to set the OSBASH
variable for the export functions to do anything.

commit_message:
Disable the RPC tests

We are going to be removing the RPC tests shortly, and the versions in
the incubator have some known concurrency issues that have been fixed in
oslo.messaging. Disable the tests here until we are ready to branch and
remove all of the RPC code entirely.

Change-Id: I385219025ea9d456c8d21e4ec6960c80bdbd1721

[{'created': '2014-09-11 02:09:33.000000000', 'message': 'Fixes AttributeError with api sample test fail

Avoid AttributeError which could be raised with api sample tests
when a string is expected but a non string type is returned
instead. This makes debugging api sample test failures easier as
the expected and actual values are displayed in the error message
rather than an AttributeError exception.

Change-Id: I4d124e4d80779c4431926619f0ca876a513a8462
'}]
commit_message:
Fixes AttributeError with api sample test fail

Avoid AttributeError which could be raised with api sample tests
when a string is expected but a non string type is returned
instead. This makes debugging api sample test failures easier as
the expected and actual values are displayed in the error message
rather than an AttributeError exception.

Change-Id: I4d124e4d80779c4431926619f0ca876a513a8462

commit_message:
Access correct key for template name

When an exception occurs while loading the config agent driver, the
handler tries to log a message, but accesses the wrong key to get the
template name. This causes another exception, which masks the original
exception.

This change accesses the correct key and performs logging inside a
with block to (defensively) preserve the exception context.

Change-Id: I3991bc4c509bbd8d68f7a1c8c8314404f2e0eafa
Closes-Bug: #1368900

commit_message:
Add unit test to os-agent API

This patch adds unit tests for os-agent API to test updating
and deleting a agent with not existing agent id.

Change-Id: Id266b0449deff6bd3715cbd2b5403031a2e34eeb

commit_message:
Use $::processorcount to compute API workers number

As we do in other OpenStack Puppet modules, let's use $::processorcount
fact to compute the number of API workers and improve scalability for
cinder-api service.

Change-Id: Iac3e1305ba0b22d70e874e038eb10914311d5695
Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>

commit_message:
Add hidden option testmode=yes to kernel args

testmode will prevent Fuel Master from
deploying. It can be used to make changes
prior to Puppet deployment.

blueprint fuel-master-ci-tests

Change-Id: If59b12a338cd6b99f8a68b4335afec519824f7de

commit_message:
Fix wrong inheritance for class HeatBaseTest

Sometimes the Sahara Platform test fails without any messages.
This bug occurs when we run Heat and Sahara Platform tests together.
If we run the Sahara test only, everything will be OK. The problem is
in wrong inheritance for class HeatBaseTest in heatmanager.py.

Change-Id: I88c4100d3603cffc4f353386490802fc6f6953b7
Closes-Bug: #1367743

commit_message:
add_node_capability and rm_node_capability unable to save changes to db

Changes to elements in existing node.properties dictionary will not get
saved to database by node.save(context) method. The properties dictionary
needs to be replaced by a new one to get the changes to be saved in the db.

Change-Id: I3bb65d00e141aedcb1278c1a700d12c9b29f7232
Closes-bug:#1371816

commit_message:
VMware: Update VMDK driver supported operations

This patch updates the list of supported operations by VMDK driver
to include volume backup/restore.

Change-Id: Ib6e23399c38b75df049450eca094d34342cd9201

commit_message:
Don't convert numeric protocol values to int

They are treated as strings everywhere. Converting them to int causes problems
when using postgresql as the database backend because it doesn't automatically
cast them back to integer.

Change-Id: I9f0a5149d24a4c003409728e50376569c97e7325
Closes-bug: 1330490
(cherry picked from commit 3be62f878e8165cf3bce357a00b8a583773f7d3b)

In a multi-node setup it is not possible to only use c-vol because
it will be tried to also start c-api, c-sch and c-bak, which will
fail.

Change-Id: Ide64d3c6b8580ce5f62ff5f17b47f37f72e9aa44
'}]
commit_message:
Check if cinder services are enabled before starting them

In a multi-node setup it is not possible to only use c-vol because
it will be tried to also start c-api, c-sch and c-bak, which will
fail.

Change-Id: Ide64d3c6b8580ce5f62ff5f17b47f37f72e9aa44

commit_message:
Do not delete properties when create image from URL

Set purge_props=False to ensure we do not delete properties that
we have set on the image.

Closes-Bug: #1325787
(cherry picked from commit I4d8a9b8b20ef946e86389c59e79e874f078e1db3)

Change-Id: I0b1db4b40e72759e85d4f15a51aef6baca863527

subject: Fixed nova VM live migration issue with 3PAR

Nova bypasses the cinder checks for a volume
being available, when it tries to attach a volume
to a new host during live migration.  The assumption
in cinder to this point has been that volumes can only
be attached to one host.  The 3PAR driver worked under
that assumption.  This assumption fell apart during detach

Cherry-pick: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/78736/11

commit_message:
Fixed nova VM live migration issue with 3PAR

Nova bypasses the cinder checks for a volume
being available, when it tries to attach a volume
to a new host during live migration.  The assumption
in cinder to this point has been that volumes can only
be attached to one host.  The 3PAR driver worked under
that assumption.  This assumption fell apart during detach
time as the driver was only looking for a VLUN on the
entire 3PAR, since it assumed it could only exist on one host.

This patch ensures that the driver looks for the VLUN on the
hostname it expects.

Closes-Bug: 1288927
(cherry picked from commit 2c1701e2f50feb5fa25ea6fb1b620f39346779de)
Cherry-pick: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/78736/11

Change-Id: I9f0044f8f1965624f1683045e18d8e4df1ce2272

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-05-12 17:57:52.000000000', 'message': 'Fixing lost vlan ids on interfaces
Backport from icehouse (60cb0911712ad11688b4d09e5c01ac39c49f5aea)
Closes-Bug: 1240849
Original fix by:
Yves-Gwenael Bourhis <yves-gwenael.bourhis@cloudwatt.com>
Original fix description:
Sometimes a vm gets its tap interface unset and reset too fast to be caught in
an agent loop, and its vlan tag was not reset.

We now detect if an interface loses its vlan tag, and if it happens the
interface will be reconfigured.

Since the TAG ID is only available via the "Port" table (in the 'tag' column),
we couldn't reuse the get_vif_port_set() method's run_vsctl call which queries
the "Interface" table, and needed a specific run_vsct call to the "Port" table
in the new get_port_tag_dict() method.

Notes about fix backport:
Icehouse renamed update_port() to scan_port() and added conception of 'updated'
ports. Original fix adding ports check_changed_vlan() found changed, but
in havana there is no 'updated' ports.

Hopefully, icehouse threaded updated ports as added in process_network_ports(),
so idea of backport is that if we add changed ports to 'added', havana's version
of process_network_ports() will do same, as icehouse's version.

Hope it will works.

Change-Id: I0bfd980019fed5754bd9e00c9d3fe2d909bf89d4

Notes about fix backport:
Icehouse renamed update_port() to scan_port() and added conception of
'updated' ports. Original fix adding ports check_changed_vlan() found
changed, but in havana there is no 'updated' ports.

Hopefully, icehouse threaded updated ports as added in
process_network_ports(), so idea of backport is that if we add
changed ports to 'added', havana's version of process_network_ports()
will do same, as icehouse's version.

Change-Id: I0bfd980019fed5754bd9e00c9d3fe2d909bf89d4

commit_message:
Fixing lost vlan ids on interfaces

Sometimes a vm gets its tap interface unset and reset too fast to be caught in
an agent loop, and its vlan tag was not reset.

We now detect if an interface loses its vlan tag, and if it happens the
interface will be reconfigured.

Since the TAG ID is only available via the "Port" table (in the 'tag' column),
we couldn't reuse the get_vif_port_set() method's run_vsctl call which queries
the "Interface" table, and needed a specific run_vsct call to the "Port" table
in the new get_port_tag_dict() method.

Change-Id: I0bfd980019fed5754bd9e00c9d3fe2d909bf89d4
Closes-Bug: 1240849

commit_message:
Show all custom properties on image detail page

Display all custom properties of a given image on the Image Detail
page. Titles for the custom properties can optionally be displayed
if they are defined in IMAGE_CUSTOM_PROPERTY_TITLES in local
settings.

(cherry picked from commit def80bef83c579114e16a0eae139ce7c1a28cecb)

Conflicts:
	openstack_dashboard/dashboards/project/images_and_snapshots/images/tabs.py

Change-Id: If97dd4a37c40d1edbc2264e298e70b14545f1dc2
Closes-Bug: #1249543

commit_message:
Don't detach root device volume

Detach a root device volume may cause various guest error. Although
we can argue that it's user response to not detach the root device
volume, a check in nova will be more helpful.

We can either give a warning message, or not allow it. This patch
forbids this operation, considering that even in real system, remove
root device does not make much sense.

Closes-Bug: #1279300

Signed-off-by: Yunhong Jiang <yunhong.jiang@intel.com>
(cherry picked from commit 7fbb42296970ee30d21bbd66b144a2ab421aa17f)

Conflicts:
	nova/tests/api/openstack/compute/contrib/test_volumes.py
	nova/tests/api/openstack/compute/plugins/v3/test_extended_volumes.py

Change-Id: I01f086be668b35442a2f139f4d7dc96884a3bda6

commit_message:
Fix broken API os-migrations

The return is not what we are expecting:
  migration-list: 'unicode' object has no attribute 'iteritems'

The conversion of the object nova.objects.MigrationList into a list
is not applied automatically.

Closes-Bug: #1260249
(cherry picked from commit 4963fa0fa0d96d8641339614438d42c81958f728)

Conflicts:

	nova/api/openstack/compute/plugins/v3/migrations.py
	nova/tests/api/openstack/compute/contrib/test_migrations.py
	nova/tests/api/openstack/compute/plugins/v3/test_migrations.py

Modified:

	nova/tests/api/openstack/compute/plugins/v3/test_migrations.py

Change-Id: I1579b1baf62275bf448f23be9465d4e9bc11ed85

commit_message:
Delete iSCSI devices after volume detached

Previously, after detaching from a volume, the iSCSI device
remains attached on the compute node until all LUNs for a given
IQN are detached -- causing issues when LUNs are reused for
different volumes. This change will delete the device(s)
associated with the detached volume so LUNs can be reused.

Conflicts:

	nova/virt/libvirt/volume.py

Fixes bug 1112483
Change-Id: Icae3ec4d1ee2036fbba7b9eb5c03a1c86014fcc0
(cherry picked from commit 8a6ee4808782820cc0938519eb3db63a5eb9a2ff)

Recently it was observed that with large numbers of volumes
that things like "cinder list" could take extremely long to
return.

For example, running cinder list on a system with 1000 volumes took
greater than 30 seconds to return.  It turns out that the cause of
this is the addition of visible admin_metadata.

There's two problems with this:
1. The original patch probably shouldn't have gone in
   data is either admin data or it's not, selectively picking
   pieces of admin data out to provide to the user just creates
   complications and introduces confusion.
2. The REAL issue here is that since the standar gets are made
   with the standard user context, the add_visible_admin_metadata
   would go through and do an elevated context get on every single
   volume individually.  This is what caused the horrible performance
   issue on cinder list with large numbers of volumes.

Running as admin, or removing the second call drops this down to about 3
seconds for the same 1000 volume list.

This patch removes the secondary admin context get_call.  Instead where
we expect to do display the visible admin_meta, we pass in a flag
requesting that the volume object we're getting has the appropriate
metadata.  This way we can elevate the context if needed and avoid
iterating through the gets again.

consolidates both V1 and V2 to use the utils method.

commit_message:
Remove second get call to list/show volumes

Recently it was observed that with large numbers of volumes
that things like "cinder list" could take extremely long to
return.

For example, running cinder list on a system with 1000 volumes took
greater than 30 seconds to return.  It turns out that the cause of
this is the addition of visible admin_metadata.

There's two problems with this:
1. The original patch probably shouldn't have gone in
   data is either admin data or it's not, selectively picking
   pieces of admin data out to provide to the user just creates
   complications and introduces confusion.
2. The REAL issue here is that since the standar gets are made
   with the standard user context, the add_visible_admin_metadata
   would go through and do an elevated context get on every single
   volume individually.  This is what caused the horrible performance
   issue on cinder list with large numbers of volumes.

Running as admin, or removing the second call drops this down to about 3
seconds for the same 1000 volume list.

This patch removes the secondary admin context get_call.  Instead where
we expect to do display the visible admin_meta, we pass in a flag
requesting that the volume object we're getting has the appropriate
metadata.  This way we can elevate the context if needed and avoid
iterating through the gets again.

This patch also cleans up the get_visible_admin_meta methods, and
consolidates both V1 and V2 to use the utils method.

Closes-Bug: 1317606

Conflicts:
	cinder/api/contrib/volume_manage.py
	cinder/api/v1/volumes.py
	cinder/api/v2/volumes.py
	cinder/tests/api/v1/test_volumes.py
	cinder/tests/api/v2/stubs.py
	cinder/tests/api/v2/test_volumes.py
	cinder/volume/api.py

Change-Id: I3fb7aefb7d8a5664b0a3fb3958f509b5cd621320
(cherry picked from commit 0505bb268942534ad5d6ecd5e34a4d9b0e7f5c04)

commit_message:
Proper port for LBaaS members

This patch set makes loadbalancer select a port on pool subnet
for new members if possible.

Conflicts:
        openstack_dashboard/dashboards/project/loadbalancers/tests.py
        openstack_dashboard/dashboards/project/loadbalancers/workflows.py

Closes-Bug: #1288859

Change-Id: I0809908ec5d15a448691dccf526b66308cf929d4
(cherry picked from commit 98bd3159d65b5d94b10403b6894002ea6de553b2)

commit_message:
Fix glance api v2 create empty image scenario

Currently, when user call glance api v2 to create an empty image,
then the image.size pollster will get an image with size=None, and
that sampe will be stored in database, then when we call
v2/samples/image.size, the wsme.exc.MissingArgument will be raised.

We should check the image.size when yield samples.

Change-Id: I4e5124cdac03eda0154d437777b17349985f067d
Closes-Bug: #1304678

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-10 11:10:26.000000000', 'message': 'Make sure that gateway is in CIDR range by default

Git commit c3706fa2 introduced the force_gateway_on_subnet
option that verified that the defined gateway is in the CIDR
range of a newly created or updated subnet. However, the default
value was False for backwards compatability reasons. The default
will change to True and the option will be marked as deprecated.

For IPv6, the gateway must be in the CIDR only if the gateway
is not a link local address.

commit_message:
Make sure that gateway is in CIDR range by default

Git commit c3706fa2 introduced the force_gateway_on_subnet
option that verified that the defined gateway is in the CIDR
range of a newly created or updated subnet. However, the default
value was False for backwards compatability reasons. The default
will change to True and the option will be marked as deprecated.

For IPv6, the gateway must be in the CIDR only if the gateway
is not a link local address.

Conflicts:
        neutron/common/config.py
        neutron/tests/unit/ml2/test_ml2_plugin.py
        neutron/tests/unit/nuage/test_nuage_plugin.py
        neutron/tests/unit/oneconvergence/test_nvsd_plugin.py
        neutron/tests/unit/test_db_plugin.py

commit_message:
Fix parameter checking about quota update api

In quota_classes and quotas update API, parameters are checked
whether they are integer or not.
But when pass float values to these APIs, error doesn't occur.
Float values should be forbidden for the following reasons.
(1)If the value that user submitted and the value registered
   actually are different, user will be confused.
(2)Error messages of these APIs are "...must be integer...".
(3)In horizon, if a float is submitted, error message is displayed.

This patch fixes this problem.

Closes-Bug: #1243037
(cherry picked from commit 01e1c027754b47239b9f9a6c40196512ec262986)

Conflicts:
	nova/api/openstack/compute/contrib/quota_classes.py
	nova/api/openstack/compute/plugins/v3/quota_classes.py
	nova/api/openstack/compute/plugins/v3/quota_sets.py
	nova/tests/api/openstack/compute/contrib/test_quota_classes.py
	nova/tests/api/openstack/compute/plugins/v3/test_quota_sets.py

Change-Id: I4c7df52ffff2d997da4e6267e25ec2ea4ab6f153

commit_message:
Add Bigswitch plugin in migration that creates 'agents' table

For creating table 'networkdhcpagentbindings' table 'agents' is
needed to exist, but Bigswitch plugin was not added to the
migration_for_plugins list in migration 511471cc46b_agent_ext_model_supp.

Closes-Bug: #1337216

commit_message:
Fix service API and cells

The move to the object model broke the service API when used together
with cells. The underlying problem is how cells will overload the id
field with a cell path to uniquely identify each service in each cell.

Changing the id to a string would defeat the purpose of the object model
so this patch uses a proxy to modify the id on access to make the
difference transparent to the API.

Closes-bug: 1251043
(cherry picked from commit 0df94733f7283cbc1e9ae7d27f5cd443158cae8e)

Conflicts:

	nova/tests/api/openstack/compute/contrib/test_services.py
	nova/tests/api/openstack/compute/plugins/v3/test_services.py

Change-Id: I165b5d64b0c1556511eb02d179ca9fc6f101c008

commit_message:
fix memory leak for _safe_log

In _safe_log it use recursive closure. The gc can not free stack for
those recursive closure for cycle-reference. So cut down the cycle
to fix it.

Change-Id: I3bd48e16fb2efd23674b7346168ad1a147019b89

[{'created': '2014-08-27 19:42:24.000000000', 'message': 'Add host_routes property to Neutron subnet resource

Template snippet that was functionally tested:

subnet:
  Type: OS::Neutron::Subnet
  Properties:
    host_routes:
    - {destination: 192.168.1.0/24, nexthop: 192.168.1.2}
    network_id: {Ref: network}
    ip_version: 4
    cidr: 10.0.3.0/24
    allocation_pools:
    - {end: 10.0.3.150, start: 10.0.3.20}

(Next hop probably would make more sense to be in the CIDR)

Change-Id: I36f72f006a1ba48a6ed55a1c361b3df8d1359caa
Closes-Bug: #1250710
Co-Authored-By: Zane Bitter <zbitter@redhat.com>
'}]
commit_message:
Add host_routes property to Neutron subnet resource

Template snippet that was functionally tested:

subnet:
  Type: OS::Neutron::Subnet
  Properties:
    host_routes:
    - {destination: 192.168.1.0/24, nexthop: 192.168.1.2}
    network_id: {Ref: network}
    ip_version: 4
    cidr: 10.0.3.0/24
    allocation_pools:
    - {end: 10.0.3.150, start: 10.0.3.20}

(Next hop probably would make more sense to be in the CIDR)

Change-Id: I36f72f006a1ba48a6ed55a1c361b3df8d1359caa
Closes-Bug: #1250710
Co-Authored-By: Zane Bitter <zbitter@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Fail if non-existent security group referenced

When using AWS::EC2::SecurityGroup resources with nova-network (not
Neutron), if a SourceSecurityGroupName was specified in a rule but the
name did not correspond to an extant security group it would be silently
ignored. This change ensures that any such error in the template will cause
creation of the security group to fail.

Closes-bug: #1291091
(cherry picked from commit 8ce9a177c47b3ee224200690d7181c784c418292)

Change-Id: I9344451c83f4184ef46d4e9906b94abda08836df

commit_message:
Segment LUN clones in NetApp iSCSI

The NetApp ZAPI for clone_create and clone_start has a maximum size.
This fix breaks the lun into consumable sizes for the ZAPI.

Closes-Bug: 1284182
Closes-Bug: 1296881
Closes-Bug: 1288962
Change-Id: Id4d0872c6099b7cfc73d806d772a3ae051a76b70
(cherry picked from commit af4a58d672cfa0c4b63015e7e783461570296c76)

commit_message:
Specify lld in tgt config backends

Otherwise when running tgt-admin --delete, it might forget
to invoke tgtadmn with "--lld iscsi" in order to delete the low-level
iscsi exports, which can cause crashes or hangs later on.

Closes-Bug: #1311640
Change-Id: I436c67c30565089236e987d84ac2609eedd2d2c7
(cherry picked from commit 872b7ca0fc5ce4911fdaadee464d46be5a38058d)

commit_message:
Don't expect nova-network is up if Neutron is used

If we use Neutron as network provider for OpenStack
cloud, nova-network service is not enabled on compute
nodes, so we should expect 14 Nova services are running
instead of 16.

Change-Id: Ie929d1c1f46dc11000c1b06469dafa5c8aaed330
Closes-bug: #1372056

commit_message:
Don't expect nova-network is up if Neutron is used

If we use Neutron as network provider for OpenStack
cloud, nova-network service is not enabled on compute
nodes, so we should expect 14 Nova services are running
instead of 16.

Change-Id: Ie929d1c1f46dc11000c1b06469dafa5c8aaed330
Closes-bug: #1372056

commit_message:
Change open(file) to with block

Currently script which loads metadata definitions to database
uses open(file) to stream files. This isn't the best practice
because in case of any errors this code may not be safe.
To solve this problem this patch changes open(file) to
'with open(file) as...:' block. It allows us to ensure that every
resource is cleaned up when the code finishes running.

Change-Id: I4a85700061ed5050f4356f1b39ea128931626c83
Closes-Bug: #1367172

I am not convinced if we should change things here as we depend on the library for http communications. Though I get the behavior you mentioned but I dont think thats a considerable problem for web servers to respond to headers.

I will suggest changes in urllib2 itself.

Second opinion is that we dont want NetApp api to be open to frequent changes unless its extremely necessary. Its our communication engine. If you feel it necessary I would recommend you modify in your own cinder installation or code branch.'}, {'account_id': 8124, 'date': '2014-09-19 15:23:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 8157, 'date': '2014-09-19 15:51:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

This change doesn't modify Netapp API. It will just send in the one HTTP request what is actually sent in the second one (the first doesn't contain Authorization header). 
As described here (urlib2 or httplib2) will not change their implementations. 
http://code.google.com/p/httplib2/issues/detail?id=130#makechanges
For a debug purpose and network monitoring I think it will be cleaner if we don't get all these 401 HTTP requests.
Furthermore modifying our own Cinder installation or code branch is impossible cause we used Openstack "Vanilla" opensource code.
Regards,'}, {'account_id': 6094, 'date': '2014-09-19 16:00:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Your change seems to be undermining opener which is responsible for header manipulations and request handling. I wont recommend patching libs in places using them.

The behavior you mentioned is a normal sequence of actions in the http world and many libs use the same kind of communication mechanism including applications which use them like those using urllib2. Network monitoring/trace data sets can be used by analyzers intelligently like clearing data wrt 401. I disagree that applications need to be modified to 1) patch libs 2) Improving network monitoring tool efficiency.'}, {'account_id': 8157, 'date': '2014-09-22 08:35:13.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

This behavior is normal for Netapp (see Navneet Singh comments)'}]

commit_message:
Netapp: set HTTP Authorization header to avoid 401 response

NetApp drivers (cmode, 7mode, iseries) have to send requests twice
in order to perform an action.
The first request is always respond with "401 Unauthorized", the
second is the same with an "Authorization" header added.
This is due to urllib2 implementation.
This patch set the "Authorization" header at the first request.
Hence HTTP requests number is divided by 2.

Closes-Bug: #1370573

Change-Id: Ia49a49b5b65c92e4e7104960d36e84076213cc12

commit_message:
Disable deploy some releases

In order to force customers moving to new releases or for technical
reasons we want to forbid deploying some releases. For this reason we
need to introduce a special field in the Relases model.

Please note, the field has no affect in experimental mode.

Change-Id: Iaf315d291ce9f18ad52b15c030be193d0d5ea6f9
Closes-Bug: #1368100

commit_message:
labs: update CirrOS image from 0.3.2 to 0.3.3

Update CirrOS image from 0.3.2 to 0.3.3. The reason for updating now is
that 0.3.3 allows setting the MTU via DHCP. Without that feature, users
would have to lower the MTU manually from the instance VM's VNC console.

Change-Id: Iee7530cb41e2a85af4a939fa004ac9e3546b6339

commit_message:
Sync glance docs with metadefs api changes

 - Rename resource_type to resource_type_
   associations in namespace API input/output
 - Add created_at/updated_at in resource_
   type_associations block of namespace API
   input/output.
 - Fix minor nits

Closes-bug: 1367908

Change-Id: Ie74bfb36a7023abb346852f5b863f19d0d7bc4ff

commit_message:
Enforce using six.text_type() over unicode()

For python 3 compatibility, this adds a hacking check to prevent the
usage of unicode().

Change-Id: I791bbf251ac0f9615a9bedc2dd295a7982d72e0a
Closes-bug: #1282893

commit_message:
Replaces assertEqual with assertTrue and assertFalse

In order to improve coding practices and be aligned to a standard,
self.assertEqual(...,True) statements where replaced with
self.assertTrue and self.assertFalse.

Change-Id: I4150a343493beae03d6f71c88e84f60d14fb60e1
Closes-Bug: #1230127

[{'created': '2014-09-13 07:38:15.000000000', 'message': "Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910
"}]
commit_message:
Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-07-03 08:27:57.000000000', 'message': 'Enabling separated sample config file generation

As a common approach most projects used now and Oslo preferred, this
change enabled sample configuration file generation mechanism for
each Glance services.

This change, as an enhancement, allows generating separated sample
configuration files for each Glance major services, e.g.:

    etc/glance-api.conf.sample
    etc/glance-cache.conf.sample
    etc/glance-manage.conf.sample
    etc/glance-registry.conf.sample
    etc/glance-scrubber.conf.sample

It is different than I94d486d6686815c45705a7a9b00fb26062e1eb63
which only supports generating an unified sample configuration
file to including all Glance available options.

This mechanism  not only can help auditing by packager, milestone
maintainer or developer as a function (testenv) of tox, but also
those separated configuration files could make deployment be easy.
And it helps keeping sample configuration files be update with
code change.

The change added "genconfigs" function as a tox testenv (-egenconfigs),
and it dependes on oslo-config-generator function of oslo.config.

The change doesn't introduce those sample files Glance repo, so
next step is to investigate if we can generate them in gate
automatically when a change was merged.

Related-Change-Id: I15686708fc9460948a58cfea3d18dae40ba1fda9
Related-Change-Id: Iae31856d5886ee78786972d80c7c103c3460a2b3

commit_message:
Enabling separated sample config file generation

As a common approach most projects used now and Oslo preferred, this
change enabled sample configuration file generation mechanism for
each Glance services.

This change, as an enhancement, allows generating separated sample
configuration files for each Glance major services, e.g.:

    etc/glance-api.conf.sample
    etc/glance-cache.conf.sample
    etc/glance-manage.conf.sample
    etc/glance-registry.conf.sample
    etc/glance-scrubber.conf.sample

It is different than I94d486d6686815c45705a7a9b00fb26062e1eb63
which only supports generating an unified sample configuration
file to including all Glance available options.

This mechanism  not only can help auditing by packager, milestone
maintainer or developer as a function (testenv) of tox, but also
those separated configuration files could make deployment be easy.
And it helps keeping sample configuration files be update with
code change.

The change added "genconfigs" function as a tox testenv (-egenconfigs),
and it dependes on oslo-config-generator function of oslo.config.

The change doesn't introduce those sample files Glance repo, so
next step is to investigate if we can generate them in gate
automatically when a change was merged.

Related-Change-Id: I15686708fc9460948a58cfea3d18dae40ba1fda9
Related-Change-Id: Iae31856d5886ee78786972d80c7c103c3460a2b3
Related-Change-Id: I76043b08e2872867e5af2a5ac902e4d092fda5c8
Closes-Bug: #1300546
Closes-Bug: #1361963

Change-Id: Ibe03a3fe80b96ca32acb1a6bea7e38e6075951bb
Signed-off-by: Zhi Yan Liu <zhiyanl@cn.ibm.com>

commit_message:
Fixing typo and improving docstring of find_domain

This should make it easier to understand the
purpose of find_domain - I believe the reason
for which find_resource wasn't enough was not
quite clear.

Change-Id: I6a1cdfa86f52401d95c6da2cd38d7c95a140b4a1

commit_message:
Delete baremetal resources in correct order

This de-randomizes the order in which baremetal resources are
deleted; foreign keys in Ironic end up requiring a certain order.

Change-Id: I3835e5e98a7520fa69157ac5d16f6d1292adb7b0
Closes-Bug: 1371755

commit_message:
Add run_cross_tests.sh script

Script `run_cross_tests.sh` can be used for running unit tests in
other projects using the current package's code.

Change-Id: Iad636216cd73d2eeb70448fda789c0ad9d579b3a
Related-Bug: #1367354

subject: Remove unused/mutable default args

commit_message:
Remove unused/mutable default args

Having mutable default args is a bad idea
(http://docs.python-guide.org/en/latest/writing/gotchas/#mutable-default-arguments).

Change-Id: I4a51c1aea04a1d2fd1e03e72a0594d2ee80eb921

commit_message:
fix memory leak for function _safe_log

In _safe_log it uses recursive closure. The gc can not free stack for
this recursive closure for cycle-reference. So cut down the cycle
to fix it.

Resolved-bug: #1365892
Change-Id: I05fbd7091b886344d76b172a5ad66d9225599d69

commit_message:
libvirt: convert encrypted LVM test to avoid DB usage

The EncryptedLvmTestCase test case was depending on the DB setup
for no purpose. This masked a bug whereby the test was relying
on the implicit import of nova.keymgr.conf_key_mgr config opts.
Explicitly import the config opt and remove DB setup. This
improves performance from 1.8s to 0.6s

Partial-bug: #1369516
Change-Id: Icd5c27b3ac6cab5a014fae65904bbbefb5343282

commit_message:
libvirt: convert test_dmcrypt to avoid DB usage

Nothing in the dmcrypt test case uses the DB, so it was
incurring the DB setup penalty for no gain. Switch to
use NoDBTestCase reducing time from 1.7s to 0.09s

Partial-bug: #1369516
Change-Id: Ifd4b919f60f48f691d83cedb6ce7ea18c98636ad

commit_message:
Add missing baremetal API tests

This adds some missing API test coverage for listing ports by
node id, node by instance uuid, node by chassis id, and listing
nodes by instance association status.  In addition to the required
client changes, this adds a common waiter for baremetal nodes which
can be leveraged in the future by the baremetal scenario tests.

Change-Id: I175da30516d697a2b3115353f405e0fe3e1ccc76

commit_message:
libvirt: convert test_blockinfo.py to avoid DB usage

Remove use of the flavour/instance DB access in the blockinfo
test case by using the Instance object instead. This speeds up
execution from approx 3 seconds to 0.3 seconds.

Partial-bug: #1369516
Change-Id: Ibb76ae64edf48012c3eddfe2eb656aa58bd198b1

commit_message:
Fix floating_ips_bulk unit test name

The unit test file name of floating_ips_bulk should be
test_floating_ips_bulk.py instead of test_floating_ip_bulk.py.

Also rename the unit test class name from 'FloatingIPBulk' to
'FloatingIpsBulk'.

Change-Id: I1d89b91083e5b567f56b27d71754a9806d668b63

Also since seach by tenant or user also needs all_tenants=1 add

Change-Id: Icc828080b400aecdb320b721c569992677848cc6

commit_message:
Add list by user to shell

Adds "--user" as a search option to the list command.

Also since seach by tenant or user also needs all_tenants=1 add
this to the seach options automatically instead of making users
remember to add it

Change-Id: Icc828080b400aecdb320b721c569992677848cc6

commit_message:
Use common code instead of novaclient.utils

Module `novaclient.utils` contains a lot of functions which are
presented in modules from common code.

* service_type -> novaclient.openstack.common.cliutils.service_type
* get_service_type -> novaclient.openstack.common.cliutils.get_service_type
* pretty_choice_list ->
      novaclient.openstack.common.cliutils.pretty_choice_list
* import_class -> oslo.utils.importutils.importclass
* HookableMixin -> novaclient.openstack.common.apiclient.base.HookableMixin

commit_message:
Add progress and cell_name into notifications

When the instance DB record is updated, we send notifications. To make
those more useful, I have added in cell_name and progress. These fields
where added after the initial notifications were added.

Change-Id: I3bc770e3b8f211c27e5e4aadd1819507d643cc75
Closes-Bug: #1366758

commit_message:
docs: Use linkcode instead of viewcode extension

Instead of viewcode extension that generates htmls from code
and links there we use linkcode extension that allows to add
links directly to git.openstack.org nicely highlighted sources.

Change-Id: I96fae99fb4a6b4204fff50ae09c8b0889ea2b76c

The pattern will be backed by DiGraph. Some interesting analysis will

commit_message:
(WIP) StateFlow pattern

Experiments for blueprint stateflow-pattern.

The pattern will be backed by DiGraph. Some interesting analysis will
be added to ensure all invariants are hold. Looks like we can't have
StateFlow in 'allways good' state -- sometimes you'll add transition
that break invariant, and then add another transition that puts
that puts everything back to good. We'll see how to express this in API.

As for engine side, the plan is to steal some ideas from
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/87417/, but do everything completely
different because I very much hope to come up with something simpler
for graph action and analyzer.

I'll be grateful if someone comes up with good more or less real-life
examples for the pattern, what I have now is too artificial.

Change-Id: I885d50dbcff1a0ae90ac8d5984400357293e016a

commit_message:
Add user.name to git config in tests

Apparently git wants the user.name set as well as user.email, so add
that to the fixture class.

Closes-Bug: #1296200
Change-Id: I6ce2d7e3ca6f0e6cf2d8de962027e8f9b9dcc9b7

commit_message:
Remove specs respository from projects.txt

There is no need for deployers to have requirements needed by a
specs repository. As such, remove the need to sync the keystone-specs
repository with global-requirements.

Change-Id: I75161791e6d2145457222dd6ccb1bcbc40d44fa5

commit_message:
BSN: Allow concurrent reads to consistency DB

Allow concurrent reads to the consistency DB since the
database lock the block was originally protecting against
is gone.

Closes-Bug: #1357102
Change-Id: I1618b4046e995c796757e723f99288e486683339
(cherry picked from commit b09c9950649c4c9fffa0b096eb21152cd84fe56f)

commit_message:
Raise a runtime error when mixed green/non-green futures

To avoid the dead-lock scenario when green futures are being
waited on in the same call as non-green futures just disallow
this rare and unlikely scenario in the first place.

Change-Id: I5b57f7aae94ae40d22047b0b085e4d99e034c2a6

This reverts commit ec57b35bc8edb933fe259db2b96c393874166dc0.

The above commit is causing odd behavior on catalog interactions based

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other

commit_message:
Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This causes docs jobs to fail because we error out on warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910

commit_message:
Refactoring HDP plugins to allow multiple Zookeeper servers

These changes are reflected in both the 1.3.2 and 2.0.6 versions of the
HDP plugin.

Changes
* fixing tests
* changing default cluster templates to allow multiple zookeeper servers
* changing zookeeper validations to allow multiple servers

Closes-Bug: #1260835
Change-Id: I5645db95ad3cb44e1d9e5db32c996280ba2d820a

commit_message:
Edits /etc/network/interface on network node

This patch edits the configuration of the interface file
to add configuration of the external bridge br-ex for the
machine to access the external network.

Change-Id: Ib14ada742ee03556ffa0cd1b1947b280574a2785
Closes-bug: 1371060

commit_message:
Updates DevStack to match Zaqar's API name change

Zaqar is a messaging service which provides support for different
messaging patterns and messaging related semantics.
This fix changes the old API name -queuing- to a more accurate name, -messaging-.

Change-Id: I07ca6ca704a4f07d88c192a5ce1a7c626de1fcea

NEUTRON_PASS instead of the correct password. Fixed.

methods (to the same values they had before).

Change-Id: I69f1dbc699b9cf3252a77c1e2f085c814ef6292f

commit_message:
labs: fix neutron admin password

In the controller node's nova.conf, neutron_admin_password was set to
NEUTRON_PASS instead of the correct password. Fixed.

Also set neutron_admin_username and neutron_admin_password via dynamic
methods (to the same values they had before).

Change-Id: I69f1dbc699b9cf3252a77c1e2f085c814ef6292f

Having said that there are a number of problems. 

'true' is not the only True value, 1, t, yes, etc are all accepted as true. There is an oslo utility somewhere that lists them all.

commit_message:
Fix the condition expression for ssl_insecure

In the existing code, self.ssl_insecure is a string. If insecure
option is set in nova api-paste.ini, whatever it is 'true' or
'false', kwargs['verify'] will become False. This commit corrects
the condition expression. This patch is backported from
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/113191/

Change-Id: I91db8e1cb39c017167a4160079846ac7c0663b03
Closes-Bug: 1353315

commit_message:
Allow scheduler pool information to be retrieved

With pool support added to Cinder, now we are kind of in an awkward
situation where we require admin to input exact location for volumes
to-be managed (imported) or migrated, which must have pool info, but
there is no way to find out what pools are there for backends except
looking at the scheduler log.  That causes bad user experience, and
thus is a bug from UX POV.

This change simply adds a new admin-api extension to allow admin to
fetch all the pool information from scheduler cache (memory), which
closes the gap for end users.

This extension provides two level of pool information: names only or
detailed information:

Pool name only:
GET http://CINDER_API_ENDPOINT/v2/TENANT_ID/scheduler-stats/get_pools

Detailed Pool info:
GET http://CINDER_API_ENDPOINT/v2/TENANT_ID/scheduler-stats/get_pools
\?detail\=True

Closes-bug: #1364279

Change-Id: I445d4e472c83db2f2d8db414de139c87d09f8fda

commit_message:
Remove duplicate test and cleanup unnecessary files

PublishErrorsHandlerTestCase is already in oslo.messaging, it
unnecessarily drags in a whole bunch of code from oslo-incubator
which is not needed for the runtime itself but needed only for
testing, so let's get rid of the crud.

Change-Id: I4df11a92a139deea3d8e68feed54f84a5196d371

commit_message:
Add _security_group_ensure_default() DBAPI method

According to the convention we use for DB API methods, every public
method should have a private counterpart. The difference between
those two is that the latter accepts an optional 'session' argument,
which makes it possible for the method to participate in the existing
database transaction.

security_group_ensure_default() was called inside instance_create()
and thus implicitly created a new concurrent db transaction, which
is now fixed by making a call to a private counterpart and passing
the session instance.

Closes-Bug: #1362233

commit_message:
Rollback quota when confirm resize concurrently completed

quota is reserved when confirm_resize is executed, if a concurrent
operation updated the status of migration, currently compute layer
will directly return back without rollback the quota and it can
lead to quota inconsistent issue layer.

Change-Id: I2217e9a4523d2783eccd8ef31c1fd65a604e2cc3
Closes-Bug: #1301690

commit_message:
the headroom infomation is incomplete

If multiple resources beyond the quotas in 'limit_check' from
nova/quota.py. The headroom information about the resources
beyond the quotas in OverQuota Exception is incomplete.

Change-Id: I790c22e3618a3558dfad64bf46e37e4e49f6385e
Closes-Bug: #1334965

commit_message:
Fix 'force' parameter for quota-update

Commit 77b4012a02c6b4827a7a6b112f35deb9ce94c395 added further
validation on the quota update controller that isn't aware of the
'force' parameter. This validation also duplicated the existing
validation that *did* honour 'force'.

This change merges the two validation methods and ensures that the
validation is skipped when the 'force' parameter is passed in the
request.

Change-Id: I25e3ce857a83cb50789a2a61bb01c796128ff4f8
Closes-bug: #1362405

commit_message:
Remove dependency on global CONF

Add a register function to be called before parsing
command line options and before calling setup to register
the command line (and other) options for logging.  Keep setup
in log.py, but change its API to take a config object as argument.

Change-Id: I0fbf81af761e0aae536e0c09b3db582fd6dbdff1

commit_message:
Timeout triggers failures running tempest for ZFSSA driver.

Adding a property to setup the RESTAPI connection timeout with
ZFS Storage Appliance, allow tempest to pass with slower network links.

DocImpact: New config parameter is added to allow configuring timeout value.
Closes-Bug: #1369136

Change-Id: I8de19f56a18106324ed414cf41ee2323de639359

commit_message:
Support 'built-in' datetime module

Some distributions (Ubuntu >= 14.10) build the datetime module
directly into the python interpreter; update tests to ensure that
this is detected correctly.

Change-Id: I67ebd2a29e695417fda0334952427fcf550738f2
Closes-Bug: 1369460

[{'created': '2014-09-13 07:36:50.000000000', 'message': "Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910
"}]
commit_message:
Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910
"}]
commit_message:
Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910

commit_message:
Add a docs virtualenv

The various projects are standardizing on a docs venv which
will eventually be called by the infra project to build the
docs for a project.

To enable our usage of this environment add a section so that
it can be called upon.

Change-Id: I420eb0d6e6f9f6f24bc493d4342478daba27ad1e

commit_message:
Fix DVR to service DHCP Ports

This fix ensures that DHCP Ports that are
available on DVR routed subnets, are serviced
by DVR neutron infrastructure.

Here servicing by DVR means, creation of
DVR namespaces on such nodes holding DHCP
Ports and also applying DVR specific OVS
Rules to the br-int and br-tun bridges on
such nodes, to enable traffic to be routed
via DVR to such DHCP Ports.

Closes-Bug: #1358718

Change-Id: Ib6d5fbf883d6698f34f3a3b722e426e3285a5736

commit_message:
Use __qualname__ if we can

Due to pep-3155 functions and methods will now have more
uniform qualified names that we can and should use when
we can (mainly applicable to python 3.x).

Once https://review.openstack.org/#/c/122495/ goes in we
can just use that module instead to get similar functionality.

Change-Id: Iea9e74aca38aa79c9294fd6e786551e91143900c

commit_message:
Raise an exception if qemu-img fails

Raise an exception if the qemu image doesn't
exist or qemu-img fails.

Co-Authored-By: Chuck Short <chuck.short@canonical.com>
Closes-Bug: #1168318
Change-Id: I6b4123590e7d2934de0bc6add900d708d5986039

commit_message:
SAML2 federated authentication for ADFS.

Authentication workflow for the Active Directory Federated Services
(ADFS) by Microsoft is different from 'standard' ECP based one.
This plugin allows for authentication and fetching security token with SAML2
assertion inside, sending to the Service Provide and retrieving an
unscoped token.

Change-Id: I588de1967a7fb92c5928686d092895847553923a
Implements: blueprint add-saml2-cli-authentication

commit_message:
Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910

commit_message:
Tunnel ID range validation for VXLAN/GRE networks

Currently, there is no check which validates the values of
tunnel range for VXLAN/GRE networks. The VXLAN VNI is 24 bit
which have range between 1 to 2^24 - 1. Similarly, GRE key field
is 32 bit which have range between 1 to 2^32 - 1.

Closes-Bug: #1306488

Co-Authored-By: romilg romilg@hp.com

Change-Id: Idb3d0f41166df589a1e90394d9319901b5f9b439

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-21 14:10:29.000000000', 'message': "Do not mark device as processed if it wasn't

Currently treat_devices_added_or_updated in the OVS agent skips
processing devices which disappeared from the integration bridge
during the agent loop.
This is fine, however the agent should not mark these devices as
processed. Otherwise they won't be processed, should they appear
again on the bridge.

This patch ensures these devices are not added to the current
device set.

The patch also changes treat_devices_added_or_updated. The
function now will return the list of skipped devices and not
anymore a flag signalling whether a resync is required.
With the current logic a resync would be required if retrieval
of device details fails. With this change, the function
treat_devices_added_or_updated will raise in this case and the
exception will be handled in process_network_ports.

For the sake of consistency, this patch also updates the
similar function treat_ancillary_devices_added in order to
use the same logic.

Finally, this patch amends an innaccurate related comment.

Closes-Bug: #1329546

Conflicts:
	neutron/plugins/openvswitch/agent/ovs_neutron_agent.py
	neutron/tests/unit/openvswitch/test_ovs_neutron_agent.py

Required changes:
- fetch all device details first before proceeding with handling ports
  to reflect Juno behaviour.

commit_message:
Do not mark device as processed if it wasn't

Currently treat_devices_added_or_updated in the OVS agent skips
processing devices which disappeared from the integration bridge
during the agent loop.
This is fine, however the agent should not mark these devices as
processed. Otherwise they won't be processed, should they appear
again on the bridge.

This patch ensures these devices are not added to the current
device set.

The patch also changes treat_devices_added_or_updated. The
function now will return the list of skipped devices and not
anymore a flag signalling whether a resync is required.
With the current logic a resync would be required if retrieval
of device details fails. With this change, the function
treat_devices_added_or_updated will raise in this case and the
exception will be handled in process_network_ports.

For the sake of consistency, this patch also updates the
similar function treat_ancillary_devices_added in order to
use the same logic.

Finally, this patch amends an innaccurate related comment.

Closes-Bug: #1329546

Conflicts:
	neutron/plugins/openvswitch/agent/ovs_neutron_agent.py
	neutron/tests/unit/openvswitch/test_ovs_neutron_agent.py

Required changes:
- fetch all device details first before proceeding with handling ports
  to reflect Juno behaviour.
- unit test was modified to run with get_device_details since
  get_devices_details_list is not available in Icehouse.
- fixed E128 violation in the backported code.

Additional changes in Havana:
- modified patch not to pass ovs_restarted argument into
  treat_devices_added_or_updated() since it's not present in Havana.
- disabled test_schedule_pool_with_down_agent that fails in gate.

Change-Id: Icc744f32494c7a76004ff161536316924594fbdb
(cherry picked from commit 90fedbe44ca6bfccce5d71465532fbdc85ee3814)
(cherry picked from commit 231010bdf22a30b2034d8221048c958544f19547)

[{'created': '2014-09-20 11:16:18.000000000', 'message': 'Revert "Style network address for subnet as required field"

This reverts commit 9f9b197fa077dabf5884242507f52528b99f1918.

The reverted commit completely breaks IPv6 network creation
workflow. In the network creation workflow, when IPv6 is selected
in "IP version", all subnet related fields will be hidden and
users cannot created a network with IPv6 subnet.

Closes-Bug: #1371901
Related-Bug: #1367858
'}]
commit_message:
Revert "Style network address for subnet as required field"

This reverts commit 9f9b197fa077dabf5884242507f52528b99f1918.

The reverted commit completely breaks IPv6 network creation
workflow. In the network creation workflow, when IPv6 is selected
in "IP version", all subnet related fields will be hidden and
users cannot created a network with IPv6 subnet.

Change-Id: I6c974ac4c890543166117253400cb6c827aa0fb8
Closes-Bug: #1371901
Related-Bug: #1367858

commit_message:
Allow hard reboots when still attempting a soft reboot

Commit cc0be157d005c5588fe5db779fc30fefbf22b44d introduced a
regression in the reboot code. Previously, a hard reboot could be
performed when an instance was in soft reboot.

This fixes the regression by allowing a hard reboot when the instance
is in one of the two new task states.

Closes-bug: 1362799

commit_message:
Add support for hypervisor type in IronicHostManager

Unlike the default HostManager the IronicHostManager doesn't pass
hypervisor attributes of the compute_node into the HostState.

Adding support for hypervisor_type makes it easy to use the
compute_capabilities filter in a combined Ironic/virt system
with a simple extra_specs value on flavors.

For completeness the following values are added:
hypervisor_type
hypervisor_version
hypervisor_version
cpu_info
supported_instances

Change-Id: I1c81bb9726597609c4e5918eb15b4f2a055e7912
Closes-Bug: #1370578

commit_message:
Remove unused config "service_down_time" reference

service_down_time was used in service API and it's not used.
It was removed at commit I1e7e8f7519ec627b96736f74ee7123d101973544.

commit_message:
Relax H305 and H307 checks

Allows third-party libs to be mixed with stdlib imports so that
new Python 3 stdlib modules can be imported as either stdlib or
third-party.

This makes these checks significantly more permissive, but it
seems like the best way to avoid any possible problems with py2/3
compatibility, while still maintaining some benefit of automated
enforcement of the import grouping rules.

Change-Id: I524b8ae3f27a6fa34483932ab255c5628e4b8b13

commit_message:
Add exists check to fetch_func_sync in libvirt imagebackend

This change adds a path exists check to fetch_func_sync to deal with
cases where a thread is waiting to acquire the lock while another
thread has the lock and is downloading the same image.  Without this
check the same image template will be downloaded multiple times.

Change-Id: Ib410903c7fd9d6954a8082391f89b42bac6a20d3
Closes-Bug: #1298420

[{'created': '2014-07-10 21:12:10.000000000', 'message': "Fix import check interaction with namespace modules

When running hacking from an oslo.* lib, all other oslo.* libs get
categorized as project because the import check was only looking at
the base module.  So when running in oslo.db, oslo.db should be
categorized as project and oslo.config as third-party, but both were
being seen as project because _get_import_type was only looking at
the 'oslo' part of the import.

This change extends _get_import_type to look at the entire module
path and adds the necessary logic for handling namespace modules
and non-module imports.  Since this is fairly complex and can't be
tested with doctests, standalone test cases are also added to verify
the behavior of the new code.

Note that prior to this change, oslo.db had 5 apparent H305
violations and 3 H307, which was incorrect.  After this change,
hacking correctly reports 3 H305 violations and 1 H307.

Also, because some of the stdlib modules don't play nice with the
new lookup method, this also includes a static list of stdlib
modules that will also be used for py2/3 compatibility in a
followup commit.

Change-Id: Ibb8c982bafcd69c9d642e86aa357a3a11b4395af

commit_message:
Fix import check interaction with namespace modules

When running hacking from an oslo.* lib, all other oslo.* libs get
categorized as project because the import check was only looking at
the base module.  So when running in oslo.db, oslo.db should be
categorized as project and oslo.config as third-party, but both were
being seen as project because _get_import_type was only looking at
the 'oslo' part of the import.

This change extends _get_import_type to look at the entire module
path and adds the necessary logic for handling namespace modules
and non-module imports.  Since this is fairly complex and can't be
tested with doctests, standalone test cases are also added to verify
the behavior of the new code.

Note that prior to this change, oslo.db had 5 apparent H305
violations and 3 H307, which was incorrect.  After this change,
hacking correctly reports 3 H305 violations and 1 H307.

Also, because some of the stdlib modules don't play nice with the
new lookup method, this also includes a static list of stdlib
modules that will also be used for py2/3 compatibility in a
followup commit.

Change-Id: Ibb8c982bafcd69c9d642e86aa357a3a11b4395af

commit_message:
XenAPI: run vhd-util repair if VHD check fails

We can hit issues with corrupted VHDs if we copy a VHD while XenServer
is performing other operations. This happens because there are times
when we copy the VHD chains while XenServer is still performing a
coalesce of the VHD chain.

In most cases, vhd-util should be able to safely repair any metadata
corruption. It can copy the copy of the VHD footer at the front of the
VHD file and add it at the bottom on the VHD file. There is no VM data
loss, due to the way the coalesce happens, but the chain will be bigger
than it would be both before and after the coalesce.

This does not, however, ensure that snapshots are valid before uploading
them to glance. But should you launch a corrupted snapshot, this change
would fix up the snapshot, and allow it to boot correctly.

Closes-Bug: #1362595

Change-Id: I88b737d7e97964a9db5ccf2c39dea7fd0701ead4

I don't like having a workaround in the unitests for specific django versions to pass, because you make the tests succeed, but I manually tested with django1.5 and confirm that the usage fails. This patch breaks what the previous patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/55702/ did for previous django versions and hide the failure in the tests.

Since we support older django versions I would prefer you to see with Romain Hardouin (author of the previous patch) of what would be the best solution.

I was thinking of e.g. replacing (instead of removing)::

    def for_url(container_name):
        """Build a URL friendly container name.
    
        Add Swift delimiter if necessary.
        The name can contain '%' (bug 1231904).
        """
        container_name = tables.wrap_delimiter(container_name)
        return utils_http.urlquote(container_name)

by (it's an example)::

    import django

    def _for_url(container_name):
        """Build a URL friendly container name.
    
        Add Swift delimiter if necessary.
        The name can contain '%' (bug 1231904).
        """
        container_name = tables.wrap_delimiter(container_name)
        return utils_http.urlquote(container_name)

    if float(django.get_version()) < 1.6:
        for_url = _for_url
    else:
        for_url = lambda x: x

In the above example I do not do the django version check in the function itself to avoid a test on each run (performance reasons). This is why I do it after definition. But it's an "example" I threw out quickly.
